{"title_page": "New Britain Bees", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox baseball team\n|  Name                 = New Britain Bees\n|  Founded              = [[2015 in baseball|2015]]\n|  Location             = [[New Britain, Connecticut]]\n|  Stadium              = [[New Britain Stadium]]\n|  Logo                 = File:NB Bees.png\n|  cap_logo             = File:NB Bees cap.png\n|  League               = [[Futures Collegiate Baseball League]]\n|  FormerLeagues        = [[Atlantic League of Professional Baseball]]\n|  retirednumbers       = 42\n|  Colors               = Black, gold, white<br />{{color box|#000}} {{color box|#FFB611}} {{color box|white}} \n|  Ownership            = Anthony Iacovone\n|  GeneralManager       = Brad Smith\n|  Manager              = \n|  Media                = New Britain Herald\n|  Mascot               = Sting\n|  Website              = {{URL|http://nbbees.com/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''New Britain Bees''' are an [[United States|American]] [[Collegiate summer baseball|collegiate summer]] [[baseball]] team based in [[New Britain, Connecticut]]. They are a member of the [[Futures Collegiate Baseball League]] (FCBL), a wood-bat league with teams in [[New Hampshire]], [[Massachusetts]], and [[Connecticut]]. Founded in October 2015, the Bees played the 2016 to 2019 seasons as an independent professional baseball team in the [[Atlantic League of Professional Baseball]]. The Bees have played all their home games at [[New Britain Stadium]], where they succeeded the [[New Britain Rock Cats]], who played in the [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] before moving to [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]], becoming the [[Hartford Yard Goats]].\n\nThe \"Bees\" name alludes to [[Beehive Field]], an older baseball park which stands next to New Britain Stadium. The civic motto of New Britain suggests, \"Industry fills the hive and enjoys the honey.\" Additionally, the civic emblem and flag incorporate a beehive as a symbol of industriousness. New Britain\u2019s official nickname is the \"Hardware City,\" referring to its industrial heritage \u2013 namely as the headquarters of [[Stanley Black & Decker]]. The former Rock Cats club, both with the \"Hardware City\" and \"New Britain\" monikers, also drew its name from manufacturing.<ref name=\"ballparkbiz\">{{cite web |title=It's the 'New Britain Bees' |url=https://ballparkbiz.wordpress.com/2015/11/05/its-the-new-britain-bees |work=Ballpark Business |date=5 Nov 2015 |accessdate=6 Nov 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Logo and colors==\nThe New Britain Bees colors are black, gold, and white. The primary logo features the \"Bees\" wordmark in a Roman font with a metallurgy-inspired serifs. The gold outline surrounding each letter alludes to honey, complete with a stylized beehive.<ref name=\"ballparkbiz\" />\n\n==History==\nIn October 2015, it was announced that New Britain would be home to a new Atlantic League team for the upcoming season.\n\nOn November 6, 2015, The Bees got their nickname. \"Bees\" was chosen after a community fan vote with a local newspaper. The other name finalists were \"Hammers\", \"Hard-Hitters\", \"Stingers\" and \"Hornets\".<ref>{{cite news |title=New Baseball Team Name is New Britain BEES |url=http://nbcityjournal.com/archives/12078 |work=New Britain City Journal |date=November 13, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171227122210/http://nbcityjournal.com/archives/12078 |archivedate=December 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn December 8, 2015, The Bees announced Patrick Day as the first General Manager in franchise history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nbbees.com/team/news/index.html?article_id=9|title=BEES ANNOUNCE PATRICK DAY AS GM|website=nbbees.com}}</ref> Day joined the Bees after previously serving as the General Manager of the [[Southern Maryland Blue Crabs]].\n\nOn December 16, 2015, [[Stan Cliburn]] was named the first manager of the team, he had previously served as manager for the [[New Britain Rock Cats]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.centralctcommunications.com/bristolpress/article_c6bff74c-a3a0-11e5-86f8-abccc29cfa1e.html|title=Former Rock Cats manager Cliburn selected to be Bees\u2019 first skipper}}</ref>\n\nOn January 10, 2017, The team announced that Patrick Day would step down as General Manager to pursue another job opportunity with the [[Fresno Grizzlies]]. Gerry Berthiaume was named as his replacement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ballparkdigest.com/2017/01/10/gerry-berthiaume-named-new-britain-bees-gm/|title=Gerry Berthiaume Named New Britain Bees GM|first=Ballpark Digest|last=Editors|date=January 10, 2017}}</ref> Berthiaume had previously been involved with professional baseball in New Britain, as he served as General Manager of the [[New Britain Red Sox]] and [[New Britain Rock Cats]].\n\nJust a week before the opener of their second season, it was announced that the Bees majority ownership was sold to a group led by Anthony Iacovone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-new-britain-bees-ownership-20170417-story.html|title=New Britain Bees Get New Owner|first=DON|last=STACOM|website=courant.com}}</ref> Iacovone is the chief executive officer of the digital advertising technology company AdTheorent. [[Frank Boulton]] and his group continue to be connected with the club as minority owners.\n\nOn September 27, 2017, The Bees announce yet another new General Manager, the third in three seasons, as Gerry Berthiaume announced his retirement from professional baseball after only one season with the Bees. Brad Smith was named the new GM after serving as the Vice President of Business Development for both the Bees and [[Bridgeport Bluefish]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hartfordbusiness.com/article/20170927/NEWS01/170929941/new-britain-bees-name-new-gm|title=New Britain Bees name new GM &#124; Hartford Business Journal}}</ref> Smith's baseball experience dates to 1995 as a concessions intern with the [[Chattanooga Lookouts]], working his way into a president/GM/ownership role from 2005-2015 with the [[Kannapolis Intimidators]]. While with Kannapolis, Smith negotiated the team's stadium lease and naming rights, as well as managed the day-to-day operations of the team and facility. He also has experience as the owner and president of the [[Wilmington Sharks]], a summer collegiate team in the [[Coastal Plain League]] from 2014 to 2016.\n\nOn November 17, 2017, it was announced that former [[New York Mets]] second baseman [[Wally Backman]] would become the second Field Manager in franchise history, replacing [[Stan Cliburn]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/wally-backman-hired-manager-independent-new-britain-bees-article-1.3637638|title=Wally Backman hired as new manager of the independent league New Britain Bees|first=Peter|last=Botte|website=nydailynews.com}}</ref> But that would only last one season. A little over a year after being named Manager of the Bees, Wally would take the open manager position with the Bees' division rival [[Long Island Ducks]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/connecticut/across-ct/popular-manager-leaves-connecticut-long-island|title=Popular Manager Leaves Connecticut For Long Island|date=November 29, 2018|website=Across Connecticut, CT Patch}}</ref>, leaving the Bees to find their third field manager in four seasons.\n\nOn January 8th, 2018, the Bees announced that New Britain native & former MLB pitcher, [[Mauro Gozzo]], would take over as field manager in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nbbees.com/team/news/index.html?article_id=1110|title=Bees Name Goose Gozzo Manager|website=nbbees.com}}</ref> Gozzo spent the 2018 season as New Britain's pitching coach under Wally Backman. Before joining the Bees coaching staff in 2018, Gozzo spent some time as a private instructor for players such as MLB pitchers [[Matt Cain]] & [[Drew Pomeranz]].\n\nIt was reported on October 3, 2019 that the Bees might no longer play in the Atlantic League come the 2020 season.<ref name=\"Ashmore\">{{cite news |last1=Ashmore |first1=Mike |title=Atlantic League Team Lineup Expected To Change In 2020, Again In 2021 |url=https://www.mycentraljersey.com/story/sports/baseball/patriots/somersetpatriotspulse/2019/10/03/atlantic-league-team-lineup-expected-to-change-in-2020-again-in-2021/40239015/ |accessdate=October 4, 2019 |work=[[MyCentralJersey.com]] |department=Somerset Patriots Pulse |date=October 3, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Chichester\">{{cite news |last1=Chichester |first1=Ryan |title=Report: New Britain Bees won't be part of Atlantic League next season, but plan to play in city in 2020 |url=http://www.newbritainherald.com/NBH-New+Britain+Bees/359170/report-new-britain-bees-wont-be-part-of-atlantic-league-next-season-but-plan-to-play-in-city-in-2020 |accessdate=October 3, 2019 |work=New Britain Herald |date=October 4, 2019}}</ref> Neither league nor team officials would comment on that, but the team's assistant general manager said, \"There will be Bees baseball in New Britain in 2020\".<ref name=\"Chichester\" /> On October 28, 2019 the Bees announced that they will be joining the [[Futures Collegiate Baseball League]] and will also be host the 2020 FCBL All-Star Game on July 14, 2020<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://nbbees.com/team/news/?article_id=1390 |title=Bees 2020 All Star Summer Schedule Announced |accessdate=October 28, 2019 |date=October 28, 2019 |publisher=New Britain Bees}}</ref>\n\n==Notable current/former players==\n\nFormer major-leaguers who have played for the Bees include: [[Cole Garner]] (2016), [[Greg Golson]] (2016), [[Eric Fornataro]] (2016-2017), [[Nick Greenwood]] (2016-2017), [[Josh Outman]] (2016, 2018), [[Scott Patterson (baseball)|Scott Patterson]] (2016), [[Josh Zeid]] (2016), [[Joe Beimel]] (2017), [[Casey Coleman]] (2017), [[Brandon League]] (2017), [[Jonathan Pettibone]] (2017-2018), [[Sammy Gervacio]] (2018-2019), [[Manny Delcarmen]] (2018), [[Zach Stewart]] (2018-2019), [[Mark Hamburger]] (2018), [[Darrell Ceciliani]] (2018), [[Reid Brignac]] (2018), Andy Van Hekken (2018), [[Alejandro De Aza]] (2019).\n\n==Season-by-season records==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"background:#FFB611;color:black\"|New Britain Bees (2016-present)\n|-\n!Season\n!Total\n!Finished\n!Playoffs\n|-\n| 2016 || 71-69   || .507  || Did not qualify for playoffs\n|-\n| 2017 || 58-81   || .417  || Did not qualify for playoffs\n|-\n| 2018 || 61-65   || .484  || Did not qualify for playoffs\n|-\n| 2019 || 72-68   || .514  || Did not qualify for playoffs\n|-\n!Totals          ||  262-281  || .480  || Totals\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://nbbees.com/ New Britain Bees] (official website)\n*[http://thefuturesleague.com/ Futures Collegiate Baseball League]\n\n{{New Britain Bees}}\n{{New Britain, Connecticut}}\n{{FCBL}}\n{{Connecticut Sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:New Britain Bees}}\n[[Category:New Britain Bees]]\n[[Category:Former Atlantic League of Professional Baseball teams]]\n[[Category:Futures Collegiate Baseball League teams]]\n[[Category:Baseball teams established in 2016]]\n[[Category:Amateur baseball teams in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:2016 establishments in Connecticut]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox baseball team\n|  Name                 = New Britain Bees\n|  Founded              = [[2015 in baseball|2015]]\n|  Location             = [[New Britain, Connecticut]]\n|  Stadium              = [[New Britain Stadium]]\n|  Logo                 = File:NB Bees.png\n|  cap_logo             = File:NB Bees cap.png\n|  League               = [[Futures Collegiate Baseball League]]\n|  FormerLeagues        = [[Atlantic League of Professional Baseball]]\n|  retirednumbers       = 42\n|  Colors               = Black, gold, white<br />{{color box|#000}} {{color box|#FFB611}} {{color box|white}} \n|  Ownership            = Anthony Iacovone\n|  GeneralManager       = Brad Smith\n|  Manager              = \n|  Media                = New Britain Herald\n|  Mascot               = Sting\n|  Website              = {{URL|http://nbbees.com/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''New Britain Bees''' are an [[United States|American]] [[Collegiate summer baseball|collegiate summer]] [[baseball]] team based in [[New Britain, Connecticut]]. They are a member of the [[Futures Collegiate Baseball League]] (FCBL), a wood-bat league with teams in [[New Hampshire]], [[Massachusetts]], and [[Connecticut]]. Founded in October 2015, the Bees played the 2016 to 2019 seasons as an independent professional baseball team in the [[Atlantic League of Professional Baseball]]. The Bees have played all their home games at [[New Britain Stadium]], where they succeeded the [[New Britain Rock Cats]], who played in the [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] before moving to [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]], becoming the [[Hartford Yard Goats]].\n\nThe \"Bees\" name alludes to [[Beehive Field]], an older baseball park which stands next to New Britain Stadium. The civic motto of New Britain suggests, \"Industry fills the hive and enjoys the honey.\" Additionally, the civic emblem and flag incorporate a beehive as a symbol of industriousness. New Britain\u2019s official nickname is the \"Hardware City,\" referring to its industrial heritage \u2013 namely as the headquarters of [[Stanley Black & Decker]]. The former Rock Cats club, both with the \"Hardware City\" and \"New Britain\" monikers, also drew its name from manufacturing.<ref name=\"ballparkbiz\">{{cite web |title=It's the 'New Britain Bees' |url=https://ballparkbiz.wordpress.com/2015/11/05/its-the-new-britain-bees |work=Ballpark Business |date=5 Nov 2015 |accessdate=6 Nov 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Logo and colors==\nThe New Britain Bees colors are black, gold, and white. The primary logo features the \"Bees\" wordmark in a Roman font with a metallurgy-inspired serifs. The gold outline surrounding each letter alludes to honey, complete with a stylized beehive.<ref name=\"ballparkbiz\" />\n\n==History==\nIn October 2015, it was announced that New Britain would be home to a new Atlantic League team for the upcoming season.\n\nOn November 6, 2015, The Bees got their nickname. \"Bees\" was chosen after a community fan vote with a local newspaper. The other name finalists were \"Hammers\", \"Hard-Hitters\", \"Stingers\" and \"Hornets\".<ref>{{cite news |title=New Baseball Team Name is New Britain BEES |url=http://nbcityjournal.com/archives/12078 |work=New Britain City Journal |date=November 13, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171227122210/http://nbcityjournal.com/archives/12078 |archivedate=December 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn December 8, 2015, The Bees announced Patrick Day as the first General Manager in franchise history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nbbees.com/team/news/index.html?article_id=9|title=BEES ANNOUNCE PATRICK DAY AS GM|website=nbbees.com}}</ref> Day joined the Bees after previously serving as the General Manager of the [[Southern Maryland Blue Crabs]].\n\nOn December 16, 2015, [[Stan Cliburn]] was named the first manager of the team, he had previously served as manager for the [[New Britain Rock Cats]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.centralctcommunications.com/bristolpress/article_c6bff74c-a3a0-11e5-86f8-abccc29cfa1e.html|title=Former Rock Cats manager Cliburn selected to be Bees\u2019 first skipper}}</ref>\n\nOn January 10, 2017, The team announced that Patrick Day would step down as General Manager to pursue another job opportunity with the [[Fresno Grizzlies]]. Gerry Berthiaume was named as his replacement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ballparkdigest.com/2017/01/10/gerry-berthiaume-named-new-britain-bees-gm/|title=Gerry Berthiaume Named New Britain Bees GM|first=Ballpark Digest|last=Editors|date=January 10, 2017}}</ref> Berthiaume had previously been involved with professional baseball in New Britain, as he served as General Manager of the [[New Britain Red Sox]] and [[New Britain Rock Cats]].\n\nJust a week before the opener of their second season, it was announced that the Bees majority ownership was sold to a group led by Anthony Iacovone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-new-britain-bees-ownership-20170417-story.html|title=New Britain Bees Get New Owner|first=DON|last=STACOM|website=courant.com}}</ref> Iacovone is the chief executive officer of the digital advertising technology company AdTheorent. [[Frank Boulton]] and his group continue to be connected with the club as minority owners.\n\nOn September 27, 2017, The Bees announce yet another new General Manager, the third in three seasons, as Gerry Berthiaume announced his retirement from professional baseball after only one season with the Bees. Brad Smith was named the new GM after serving as the Vice President of Business Development for both the Bees and [[Bridgeport Bluefish]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hartfordbusiness.com/article/20170927/NEWS01/170929941/new-britain-bees-name-new-gm|title=New Britain Bees name new GM &#124; Hartford Business Journal}}</ref> Smith's baseball experience dates to 1995 as a concessions intern with the [[Chattanooga Lookouts]], working his way into a president/GM/ownership role from 2005-2015 with the [[Kannapolis Intimidators]]. While with Kannapolis, Smith negotiated the team's stadium lease and naming rights, as well as managed the day-to-day operations of the team and facility. He also has experience as the owner and president of the [[Wilmington Sharks]], a summer collegiate team in the [[Coastal Plain League]] from 2014 to 2016.\n\nOn November 17, 2017, it was announced that former [[New York Mets]] second baseman [[Wally Backman]] would become the second Field Manager in franchise history, replacing [[Stan Cliburn]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/wally-backman-hired-manager-independent-new-britain-bees-article-1.3637638|title=Wally Backman hired as new manager of the independent league New Britain Bees|first=Peter|last=Botte|website=nydailynews.com}}</ref> But that would only last one season. A little over a year after being named Manager of the Bees, Wally would take the open manager position with the Bees' division rival [[Long Island Ducks]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/connecticut/across-ct/popular-manager-leaves-connecticut-long-island|title=Popular Manager Leaves Connecticut For Long Island|date=November 29, 2018|website=Across Connecticut, CT Patch}}</ref>, leaving the Bees to find their third field manager in four seasons.\n\nOn January 8th, 2018, the Bees announced that New Britain native & former MLB pitcher, [[Mauro Gozzo]], would take over as field manager in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nbbees.com/team/news/index.html?article_id=1110|title=Bees Name Goose Gozzo Manager|website=nbbees.com}}</ref> Gozzo spent the 2018 season as New Britain's pitching coach under Wally Backman. Before joining the Bees coaching staff in 2018, Gozzo spent some time as a private instructor for players such as MLB pitchers [[Matt Cain]] & [[Drew Pomeranz]].\n\nIt was reported on October 3, 2019 that the Bees might no longer play in the Atlantic League come the 2020 season.<ref name=\"Ashmore\">{{cite news |last1=Ashmore |first1=Mike |title=Atlantic League Team Lineup Expected To Change In 2020, Again In 2021 |url=https://www.mycentraljersey.com/story/sports/baseball/patriots/somersetpatriotspulse/2019/10/03/atlantic-league-team-lineup-expected-to-change-in-2020-again-in-2021/40239015/ |accessdate=October 4, 2019 |work=[[MyCentralJersey.com]] |department=Somerset Patriots Pulse |date=October 3, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Chichester\">{{cite news |last1=Chichester |first1=Ryan |title=Report: New Britain Bees won't be part of Atlantic League next season, but plan to play in city in 2020 |url=http://www.newbritainherald.com/NBH-New+Britain+Bees/359170/report-new-britain-bees-wont-be-part-of-atlantic-league-next-season-but-plan-to-play-in-city-in-2020 |accessdate=October 3, 2019 |work=New Britain Herald |date=October 4, 2019}}</ref> Neither league nor team officials would comment on that, but the team's assistant general manager said, \"There will be Bees baseball in New Britain in 2020\".<ref name=\"Chichester\" /> On October 28, 2019 the Bees announced that they will be joining the [[Futures Collegiate Baseball League]] and will also be host the 2020 FCBL All-Star Game on July 14, 2020<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://nbbees.com/team/news/?article_id=1390 |title=Bees 2020 All Star Summer Schedule Announced |accessdate=October 28, 2019 |date=October 28, 2019 |publisher=New Britain Bees}}</ref>\n\n==Notable current/former players==\n\nFormer major-leaguers who have played for the Bees include: [[Cole Garner]] (2016), [[Greg Golson]] (2016), [[Eric Fornataro]] (2016-2017), [[Nick Greenwood]] (2016-2017), [[Josh Outman]] (2016, 2018), [[Scott Patterson (baseball)|Scott Patterson]] (2016), [[Josh Zeid]] (2016), [[Joe Beimel]] (2017), [[Casey Coleman]] (2017), [[Brandon League]] (2017), [[Jonathan Pettibone]] (2017-2018), [[Sammy Gervacio]] (2018-2019), [[Manny Delcarmen]] (2018), [[Zach Stewart]] (2018-2019), [[Mark Hamburger]] (2018), [[Darrell Ceciliani]] (2018), [[Reid Brignac]] (2018), Andy Van Hekken (2018), [[Alejandro De Aza]] (2019),.\n\n==Season-by-season records==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"background:#FFB611;color:black\"|New Britain Bees (2016-present)\n|-\n!Season\n!Total\n!Finished\n!Playoffs\n|-\n| 2016 || 71-69   || .507  || Did not qualify for playoffs\n|-\n| 2017 || 58-81   || .417  || Did not qualify for playoffs\n|-\n| 2018 || 61-65   || .484  || Did not qualify for playoffs\n|-\n| 2019 || 72-68   || .514  || Did not qualify for playoffs\n|-\n!Totals          ||  262-281  || .480  || Totals\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://nbbees.com/ New Britain Bees] (official website)\n*[http://thefuturesleague.com/ Futures Co