{"title_page": "History of the Czechs in Vienna", "text_new": "{{Ethnic Vienna sidebar}}\n{{Czechs}}\n\nThe city of [[Vienna]], [[Austria]] once included a large [[Czechs|Czech]] population.\n\n==History==\nAround the start of the 20th century, Vienna ([[Czech language|Czech]] ''V\u00edde\u0148'', [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] ''B\u00e9cs'') was the city with the second-largest [[Czechs|Czech]] population in the world (after [[Prague]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wieninternational.at/en/node/3586 |title=Czech and Slovak roots in Vienna |publisher=Wieninternational.at |accessdate=2014-05-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512221406/http://www.wieninternational.at/en/node/3586 |archivedate=2014-05-12 }}</ref> At its peak, in 1900, out of 1,674,957 inhabitants of Vienna, 102,974 people claimed Czech or Slovak as their colloquial language. However, as  Umgangssprache (everyday language) was not properly defined by the Austrian authorities, there are claims that the Czech minority numbered as high as 250,000-300,000, making Vienna a city with the second largest Czech speaking population, only after Prague.<ref>Official census 1900</ref> After World War I, many [[Czechs]] and also nationalities returned to their ancestral countries, resulting in a decline in the Viennese population.  After World War II, the Soviets used force to repatriate key workers of Czech and Hungarian origins to return to their ethnic homelands to further the Soviet bloc economy.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Czech print media in Vienna]]\n*[[Czech schools in Vienna]]\n\n*[[:cs:\u010ce\u0161i ve V\u00eddni]], Czech Wikipedia version of this article.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Basler, Helena. ''V\u00edde\u0148\u0161t\u00ed \u010ce\u0161i 1945-2005 : k d\u011bjin\u00e1m n\u00e1rodnostn\u00ed men\u0161iny = Die Wiener Tschechen 1945-2005 : zur Geschichte einer Volksgruppe'', Wien ; Praha : \u010cesk\u00e9 kulturn\u011bhistorick\u00e9 centrum, 2006-.\n* Baslerov\u00e1, Helena; Kulturn\u00ed klub \u010cech\u016f a Slov\u00e1k\u016f v Rakousku. ''Die Wiener Tschechen 1945-2005 : zur Geschichte einer Volksgruppe'', Wien : Tschechisches kulturhistorisches Institut ; Praha : KLP - Koniasch Latin Press, 2006-.\n* Bernas, Karl. ''Sokol Favoriten'', Wien : Museumsverein Favoriten, 2000.\n* Brousek, Karl M. ''Wien und seine Tschechen : Integration und Assimilation einer Minderheit im 20. Jahrhundert'', M\u00fcnchen : Oldenbourg, 1980.\n* Glettler, Monika. ''B\u00f6hmisches Wien'', Wien : Herold, 1985.\n* Glettler, Monika. ''Sokol und Arbeiterturnvereine (D.T.J.) der Wiener Tschechen bis 1914.'', M\u00fcnchen, Wien, Oldenbourg, 1970.\n* Lutz, Freddy. ''B\u00f6hmische Emigranten'', Wien : F. Lutz, 1993.\n* Hauner, Milan. ''The Czechs in Vienna around 1900. Structural Analysis of a National Minority in a Metropolis'', Philosophy and History, v8 n2 (1975); 264\u2013266.\n* Martin, Otto. ''Das tschechische Schulwesen in Wien'', (Salzburg) (Druck von R. Kiesel), 1924.\n* Vale\u0161, Vlasta. ''Die wiener Tschechen, einst und jetzt : eine Einf\u00fchrung in Geschichte und Gegenwart der tschechischen Volksgruppe in Wien = V\u00edde\u0148\u0161t\u00ed \u010de\u0161i v\u010dera a dnes : \u00favod do d\u011bjin a sou\u010dasnosti \u010desk\u00e9 n\u00e1rodnostn\u00ed skupiny ve V\u00eddni'', Praha : Scriptorium, 2004.\n* Wonisch, Regina. ''Tschechen in Wien : zwischen nationaler Selbstbehauptung und Assimilation'', Wien : L\u00f6cker, 2010.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://summit.sfu.ca/system/files/iritems1/8621/b36181110.pdf The German National Attack on the Czech Minority in Vienna]\n\n{{Czech diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:Czechs in Vienna| ]]\n[[Category:History of Vienna|Czechs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Ethnic Vienna sidebar}}\n{{Czechs}}\n\nThe city of [[Vienna]], [[Austria]] once included a large [[Czechs|Czech]] population.\n\n==History==\nAround the start of the 20th century, Vienna ([[Czech language|Czech]] ''V\u00edde\u0148'', [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] ''B\u00e9cs'') was the city with the second-largest [[Czechs|Czech]] population in the world (after [[Prague]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wieninternational.at/en/node/3586 |title=Czech and Slovak roots in Vienna |publisher=Wieninternational.at |accessdate=2014-05-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512221406/http://www.wieninternational.at/en/node/3586 |archivedate=2014-05-12 }}</ref> At its peak, in 1900, out of 1,674,957 inhabitants of Vienna, 102,974 people claimed Czech or Slovak as their colloquial language. However, as  Umgangssprache (everyday language) was not properly defined by the Austrian authorities, there are claims that the Czech minority numbered as high as 250,000-300,000, making Vienna a city with the second largest Czech speaking population, only after Prague.<ref>Official census 1900</ref> After World War I, many [[Czechs]] and also nationalities returned to their ancestral countries, resulting in a decline in the Viennese population.  After World War II, the Soviets used force to repatriate key workers of Czech and Hungarian origins to return to their ethnic homelands to further the Soviet bloc economy.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Czech print media in Vienna]]\n*[[Czech schools in Vienna]]\n\n*[[:cs:\u010ce\u0161i ve V\u00eddni]], Czech Wikipedia version of this article.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Basler, Helena. ''V\u00edde\u0148\u0161t\u00ed \u010ce\u0161i 1945-2005 : k d\u011bjin\u00e1m n\u00e1rodnostn\u00ed men\u0161iny = Die Wiener Tschechen 1945-2005 : zur Geschichte einer Volksgruppe'', Wien ; Praha : \u010cesk\u00e9 kulturn\u011bhistorick\u00e9 centrum, 2006-.\n* Baslerov\u00e1, Helena; Kulturn\u00ed klub \u010cech\u016f a Slov\u00e1k\u016f v Rakousku. ''Die Wiener Tschechen 1945-2005 : zur Geschichte einer Volksgruppe'', Wien : Tschechisches kulturhistorisches Institut ; Praha : KLP - Koniasch Latin Press, 2006-.\n* Bernas, Karl. ''Sokol Favoriten'', Wien : Museumsverein Favoriten, 2000.\n* Brousek, Karl M. ''Wien und seine Tschechen : Integration und Assimilation einer Minderheit im 20. Jahrhundert'', M\u00fcnchen : Oldenbourg, 1980.\n* Glettler, Monika. ''B\u00f6hmisches Wien'', Wien : Herold, 1985.\n* Glettler, Monika. ''Sokol und Arbeiterturnvereine (D.T.J.) der Wiener Tschechen bis 1914.'', M\u00fcnchen, Wien, Oldenbourg, 1970.\n* Lutz, Freddy. ''B\u00f6hmische Emigranten'', Wien : F. Lutz, 1993.\n* Hauner, Milan. ''The Czechs in Vienna around 1900. Structural Analysis of a National Minority in a Metropolis'', Philosophy and History, v8 n2 (1975); 264-266.\n* Martin, Otto. ''Das tschechische Schulwesen in Wien'', (Salzburg) (Druck von R. Kiesel), 1924.\n* Vale\u0161, Vlasta. ''Die wiener Tschechen, einst und jetzt : eine Einf\u00fchrung in Geschichte und Gegenwart der tschechischen Volksgruppe in Wien = V\u00edde\u0148\u0161t\u00ed \u010de\u0161i v\u010dera a dnes : \u00favod do d\u011bjin a sou\u010dasnosti \u010desk\u00e9 n\u00e1rodnostn\u00ed skupiny ve V\u00eddni'', Praha : Scriptorium, 2004.\n* Wonisch, Regina. ''Tschechen in Wien : zwischen nationaler Selbstbehauptung und Assimilation'', Wien : L\u00f6cker, 2010.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://summit.sfu.ca/system/files/iritems1/8621/b36181110.pdf The German National Attack on the Czech Minority in Vienna]\n\n{{Czech diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:Czechs in Vienna| ]]\n[[Category:History of Vienna|Czechs]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 264-266 \u2192 264\u2013266", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Czechs_in_Vienna"}
{"title_page": "Ryukyuans in Brazil", "text_new": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group            = Ryukyuans in Brazil\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| languages        = [[Brazilian Portuguese]], [[Ryukyuan languages]]\n| religions        = [[Catholicism]], [[Ryukyuan religion]]\n| related_groups   = [[Ryukyuan people]]\n| population       = 170,000\n}}\n\nThe '''Ryukyuans in Brazil''' are [[Brazilians|Brazilian]] nationals of [[Ryukyuan people|Ryukyuan]] descent.\n\n== History ==\nMany people were struggling economically in the [[Ryukyu Islands]] during the late 1800s and early 1900s. As a result, many Ryukyuans emigrated elsewhere to places such as [[Brazil]], [[Peru]], [[Hawaii]] and [[mainland Japan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.discovernikkei.org/en/journal/2015/8/18/okinawan-1/|title=Immigration\u2014Missing Link in Japanese History: Why Are There So Many Okinawan Immigrants? \u2013 Part 1|last=Aug 2015|first=Mina Otsuka / 18|website=Discover Nikkei|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn June 18, 1908, the first migrants from [[Japan]] arrived at the port of [[Santos, S\u00e3o Paulo|Santos]] in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]]. Half of these migrants were [[Okinawan people|Okinawans]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-42859249|title=A little corner of Brazil that is forever Okinawa|date=2018-02-04|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB}}</ref>. Immigration from the Ryukyu Islands to Brazil would continue in the following years.\n\n== Demographics ==\nRyukyuans in Brazil make up 9.4% (170,000) of the entire Brazilian [[Japanese diaspora|Nikkei]] community (1,600,000), despite Ryukyuans making up only 1% of Japan's total population.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Nikkei communities in neighboring [[Peru]] and [[Argentina]] are majority Ryukyuan-descended.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe majority of Ryukyuans in South America specifically belong to the [[Okinawan people|Okinawan]] subgroup.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Ryukyuan people]]\n* [[Ryukyuan diaspora]]\n* [[Ryukyu Islands]]\n* [[Japanese Brazilians]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}{{Brazil-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Ryukyuan people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group            = Ryukyuans in Brazil\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| languages        = [[Brazilian Portuguese]], [[Ryukyuan languages]]\n| religions        = [[Catholicism]], [[Ryukyuan religion]]\n| related_groups   = [[Ryukyuan people]]\n| population       = 170,000\n}}\n\nThe '''Ryukyuans in Brazil''' are [[Brazilians|Brazilian]] nationals of [[Ryukyuan people|Ryukyuan]] descent.\n\n== History ==\nMany people were struggling economically in the [[Ryukyu Islands]] during the late 1800s and early 1900s. As a result, many Ryukyuans emigrated elsewhere to places such as [[Brazil]], [[Peru]], [[Hawaii]] and [[mainland Japan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.discovernikkei.org/en/journal/2015/8/18/okinawan-1/|title=Immigration\u2014Missing Link in Japanese History: Why Are There So Many Okinawan Immigrants? \u2013 Part 1|last=Aug 2015|first=Mina Otsuka / 18|website=Discover Nikkei|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn June 18, 1908, the first migrants from [[Japan]] arrived at the port of [[Santos, S\u00e3o Paulo|Santos]] in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]]. Half of these migrants were [[Okinawan people|Okinawans]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-42859249|title=A little corner of Brazil that is forever Okinawa|date=2018-02-04|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB}}</ref>. Immigration from the Ryukyu Islands to Brazil would continue in the following years.\n\n== Demographics ==\nRyukyuans in Brazil make up 9.4% (170,000) of the entire Brazilian [[Japanese diaspora|Nikkei]] community (1,600,000), despite Ryukyuans making up only 1% of Japan's total population.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Nikkei communities in neighboring [[Peru]] and [[Argentina]] are majority Ryukyuan-descended.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe majority of Ryukyuans in South America specifically belong to the [[Okinawan people|Okinawan]] subgroup.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Ryukyuan people]]\n* [[Ryukyuan diaspora]]\n* [[Ryukyu Islands]]\n* [[Japanese Brazilians]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}{{Brazil-stub}}\n\n{{Categories:Ryukyuan people}}\n", "name_user": "Coastaline", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ryukyuans_in_Brazil"}
{"title_page": "Starship Troopers (film)", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = October 2019}}\n{{short description|1997 military science fiction movie directed by Paul Verhoeven}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Starship Troopers\n| image          = Starship Troopers - movie poster.jpg\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Paul Verhoeven]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jon Davison (film producer)|Jon Davison]]\n* [[Alan Marshall (producer)|Alan Marshall]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = [[Edward Neumeier]]\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Starship Troopers]]''|[[Robert A. Heinlein]]}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Casper Van Dien]]\n* [[Dina Meyer]]\n* [[Denise Richards]]\n* [[Jake Busey]]\n* [[Neil Patrick Harris]]\n* [[Patrick Muldoon]]\n* [[Michael Ironside]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Basil Poledouris]]\n| cinematography = [[Jost Vacano]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mark Goldblatt]]\n* Caroline Ross\n}}\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[TriStar Pictures]]\n* [[Touchstone Pictures]]\n* [[Jon Davison (film producer)|Jon Davison Productions]]\n}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Sony Pictures Releasing]] {{small|(North America)}}\n*[[Buena Vista International]] {{small|(International)}}\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|1997|11|07}}\n| runtime        = 129 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $105 million<ref name=\"boxofficemojo\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=starshiptroopers.htm|title=Starship Troopers|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref>\n| gross          = $121.2 million<ref name=\"boxofficemojo\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Starship Troopers''''' is a 1997 American [[Satire|satirical]] [[military science fiction]] [[action film]] directed by [[Paul Verhoeven]] and written by [[Edward Neumeier]]. It originally came from an unrelated script called ''Bug Hunt at Outpost Nine'',<ref name=\"Robley\">{{cite journal|last=Robley|first=Les Paul|date=November 1997|title=Interstellar Exterminators. Ornery insects threaten the galaxy in Starship Troopers|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1P3-1504299331/interstellar-exterminators|journal=[[American Cinematographer]]|publisher=[[American Society of Cinematographers]]|volume=78|issue=11|pages=56\u201366}}{{subscription required|via=[[Questia Online Library]]}}</ref> but eventually licensed the name ''[[Starship Troopers]]'' from the [[science fiction]] [[Starship Troopers|novel]] by [[Robert A. Heinlein]]. The story follows a young soldier named Johnny Rico and his exploits in the Mobile Infantry, a futuristic military unit. Rico's military career progresses from [[Army recruit|recruit]] to [[non-commissioned officer]] and finally to [[Officer (armed forces)|officer]] against the backdrop of an interstellar war between mankind and an insectoid species known as \"Arachnids\".\n\nThe only theatrically released film in the [[Starship Troopers (franchise)|''Starship Troopers'' film series]], it received mostly negative reviews from critics upon release<ref name=\"The Atlantic\"/> but has garnered a more mixed reception in retrospect. It grossed $54.5 million in the US and a total of $121.2 million worldwide against its budget of $105 million.<ref name=\"boxofficemojo\"/> The film was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects]] at the [[70th Academy Awards]] in 1998. In 2012, ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' ranked the film #20 on its list of the 100 Best Films of the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/feature/the-100-best-films-of-the-1990s/334/page_9|title=The 100 Best Films of the 1990s|date=November 5, 2012|website=[[Slant Magazine]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111231924/http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/feature/the-100-best-films-of-the-1990s/334/page_9|archive-date=November 11, 2012|accessdate=June 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Per [[WP:FILMPLOT]], film plots should be between 400 and 700 words. -->\nIn the 23rd century, while colonizing new planets, humans have encountered a hostile non-technological insectoid species known as Arachnids or \"[[Bug (Starship Troopers)|Bugs]]\".\n\nIn the United Citizen Federation, citizenship is earned by performing activities such as military service, which grants individuals opportunities prohibited to basic civilians. After graduating from high school in [[Buenos Aires]], [[Juan Rico|John \"Johnny\" Rico]], his girlfriend Carmen Iba\u00f1ez, and [[psychic]] best friend Carl Jenkins enlist in the Federal Service, despite Rico's parents' disapproval of military service. Carmen becomes a spaceship pilot, while Carl joins [[Military Intelligence]]. Rico enlists in the Mobile Infantry and is surprised to find Isabelle \"Dizzy\" Flores, his fellow ex-student, has deliberately transferred to his squad.\n\nIn Mobile Infantry basic training, Career Sgt Zim ruthlessly trains the recruits. Rico befriends fellow cadet Ace Levy and is later promoted to squad leader. He subsequently receives a [[Dear John letter]] from Carmen, as she desires a career with the fleet and now serves under Rico's high-school sports rival, Zander Barcalow. Following a [[Live fire exercise|live-fire training]] incident that kills one of Rico's squad members and causes another to quit out of guilt, Rico is demoted and [[Flagellation|flogged]]. He resigns and calls his parents to ask them if he can return home, but rescinds his resignation after an asteroid, reported to be launched by the Arachnids, obliterates Buenos Aires, killing his mother and millions of others.\n\nAn invasion force is deployed to [[Klendathu]], the Arachnids' home planet, but the operation severely underestimates the Arachnids and is a total disaster. Rico is severely wounded and mistakenly reported [[killed in action|KIA]]. After recovering, he, Ace, and Dizzy are reassigned to the \"Roughnecks\", an [[Special forces|elite unit]] commanded by Lt. Jean Rasczak, Rico's former high-school teacher. He quickly gains the respect of his peers and is promoted to the rank of Corporal after taking out a tanker bug. His relationship with Dizzy continues to grow, and they have sex during their night on Tango Urilla.\n\nThe Roughnecks respond to a distress call from Planet \"P\", where they reconnoiter an outpost that has been devastated by Bugs. They soon realize that the distress call is a trap, and the Arachnids swarm the outpost. Rico, now an acting sergeant, euthanizes a mortally wounded Rasczak after a buried Bug bites off his legs. Dizzy is killed, but the surviving Roughnecks are rescued by Carmen and Zander. Rico and Carmen encounter Carl, now a high-ranking intelligence officer, at Dizzy's funeral. Carl reveals that there is reason to believe an intelligent \"brain bug\" is directing the other Bugs and has been learning how to fight humans. He [[Battlefield promotion|field-promotes]] Rico to lieutenant and gives him command of the Roughnecks, ordering the Mobile Infantry units under his control to return to \"P\" in an attempt to capture the brain bug.\n\nThe Fleet encounters unexpected heavy fire from the Bugs and Carmen's ship is destroyed. Carmen and Zander's escape pod crashes into a Bug tunnel system near Rico. They are surrounded by Bugs and a brain bug uses its [[proboscis]] to pierce Zander's skull and eat his brain. As it is about to do the same to Carmen, she cuts off its proboscis with a knife. Rico, Watkins and Ace arrive and threaten the Bugs with a small [[Tactical nuclear weapon|nuclear bomb]], which the brain bug recognizes. They flee while the brain bug makes its escape. Arachnids pursue them and Watkins, mortally wounded, sacrifices himself by detonating the bomb to enable the others to escape.\n\nAfter returning to the surface, they find that former Sergeant Zim, who had requested a demotion to private so that he could serve at the front, has captured the brain bug. Carl tells Rico and Carmen that the humans will soon be victorious now that Military Intelligence can study the brain bug. Carl mentally scans the Bug and reveals that it is afraid, to the cheers of the troops. A [[propaganda]] clip shows Carmen, Ace, and Rico as model servicemen, encouraging viewers to enlist in the armed forces.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=27em}}\n* [[Casper Van Dien]] as [[John Rico|Pvt./Cpl./Sgt./Lt. John \"Johnny\" Rico]]\n* [[Dina Meyer]] as Pvt. Isabelle \"Dizzy\" Flores\n* [[Denise Richards]] as Lt./Capt. Carmen Iba\u00f1ez\n* [[Jake Busey]] as Pvt. Ace Levy\n* [[Neil Patrick Harris]] as Col. Carl Jenkins\n* [[Patrick Muldoon]] as Lt. Zander Barcalow\n* [[Clancy Brown]] as Career Sgt./Pvt. Zim\n* [[Michael Ironside]] as Lt. Jean Rasczak\n* [[Seth Gilliam]] as Cpl. Sugar Watkins\n* [[Bruce Gray]] as Sky Marshal Dienes\n* [[Marshall Bell]] as General Owen\n* [[Eric Bruskotter]] as Private Breckinridge\n* [[Brenda Strong]] as Captain Deladier\n* [[Christopher Curry (actor)|Christopher Curry]] as Bill Rico\n* [[Lenore Kasdorf]] as Mrs. Rico\n* Denise Dowse as Sky Marshal Meru\n* [[Amy Smart]] as Pilot Cadet/Lt. Lumbreiser\n* [[Dean Norris]] as Commanding officer\n* [[Rue McClanahan]] as Biology teacher\n* [[Dale Dye]] as Unnamed general\n* [[Anthony Ruivivar]] as Shujumi\n* [[Robert David Hall]] as [[Recruiter]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Background==\n\n===Production===\n[[Image:HellsHalfAcre.JPG|thumb|right|Badlands of [[Hell's Half Acre (Wyoming)|Hell's Half Acre]], Natrona County, Wyoming, where parts of ''Starship Troopers'' were filmed.]]\nThe film started life as a script called ''Bug Hunt at Outpost Nine''.<ref name=\"Robley\"/> When similarities, especially the \"bugs\", were pointed out between this and the novel ''[[Starship Troopers]]'', plans were made to license the rights to the book and tweak character names and circumstances to match. [[Paul Verhoeven]] had never read the book, and attempted to read it for the film, but it made him \"bored and depressed\", so he read only a few chapters:\n\n<blockquote>I stopped after two chapters because it was so boring \u2026 It is really quite a bad book. I asked [[Edward Neumeier|Ed Neumeier]] to tell me the story because I just couldn't read the thing. It's a very right-wing book.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/paul-verhoeven/|title=Triple Dutch: Paul Verhoeven's sci-fi trilogy|last1=Smith|first1=Adam|last2=Williams|first2=Owen|date=February 12, 2015|website=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|url-status=dead|accessdate=December 7, 2016|quote=I stopped after two chapters because it was so boring,\" says Verhoeven of his attempts to read Heinlein's opus. \"It is really quite a bad book. I asked Ed Neumeier to tell me the story because I just couldn't read the thing. It's a very right-wing book. And with the movie we tried, and I think at least partially succeeded, in commenting on that at the same time. It would be eat your cake and have it. All the way through we were fighting with the fascism, the ultra-militarism. All the way through I wanted the audience to be asking, 'Are these people crazy?'}}</ref>{{Dead link|date=October 2019}}</blockquote>\n\nNeumeier had previously worked with Verhoeven as a writer on ''[[RoboCop|Robocop]]'' (1987).\n\nThe \"bug planet\" scenes were filmed in the [[badlands]] of [[Hell's Half Acre (Wyoming)|Hell's Half Acre]] in [[Natrona County]], Wyoming.<ref name=\"audiocommentary\" />\n\nTwo nude scenes were kept in the original version (the co-ed shower and a bedroom romp between Rico and Dizzy), although these were modified in the broadcast version. The cast agreed to do the co-ed shower scene only if Verhoeven agreed to direct the scene naked, which he did.<ref name=\"audiocommentary\"/>\n\nIn the [[audio commentary]] on the DVD or Blu-ray release, Verhoeven remarks that he had hoped to cast actors whose age more closely matched that of the characters\u2014and indeed of real-world soldiers\u2014but that the producers felt such actors would look too young. The teacher and leader of the \"Roughnecks\" in the novel are combined into one role played by Ironside.<ref name=\"audiocommentary\"/>\n\nTest audience reactions led to several minor changes before the film was released. Originally, it was clear that Carmen was torn between Rico and Zander. Test audiences, regardless of gender, strongly felt that a woman could not love two men at once, so scenes which portrayed this were cut. These audiences also felt it was immoral for Carmen to choose a career ahead of being loyal to Rico, to the extent that many commented that, in so doing, Carmen should have been the one to die instead of Dizzy. While admitting it may have been a bad commercial decision not to change the film to accommodate this, the producer and director did cut a scene from after Zander's death in which Carmen and Rico kiss, which the audience believed made the previous betrayal even more immoral.<ref name=\"audiocommentary\"/>\n\n===Relationship to novel===\nBecause the film originated from an unrelated script, with names and superficial details from the [[Starship Troopers|novel]] being added retroactively, there are many differences between the two.<ref name=\"gemsbok\">{{Cite web|url=http://thegemsbok.com/art-reviews-and-articles/thursday-theater-starship-troopers-paul-verhoeven-robert-heinlein/|title=Poking Fun at Militarism: How Paul Verhoeven\u2019s Cult Classic ''Starship Troopers'' Willfully Discards Robert Heinlein\u2019s Novel|last=Podgorski|first=Daniel|date=February 4, 2016|website=The Gemsbok|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref> While the novel has [[Starship Troopers#Controversy|been accused of]] promoting militarism, fascism, and military rule,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/2.10/godwin.if.html|title=Meme, Counter-meme|last=Godwin|first=Mike|date=October 1, 1994|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nitrosyncretic.com/pdfs/nature_of_fedsvc_1996.pdf|title=The Nature of \"Federal Service\" in Robert A. Heinlein\u2019s ''Starship Troopers''|last=Gifford|first=James|date=|year=2011|website=Nitrosyncretic Press|publisher=|orig-year=1986|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref> the film satirizes these concepts by featuring bombastic displays of nationalism as well as news reports that are intensely [[xenophobia|xenophobic]] and [[propaganda|propagandistic]].<ref name=\"gemsbok\"/>\n\nVerhoeven stated in 1997 that the first scene of the film\u2014an advertisement for the Mobile Infantry\u2014was adapted shot-for-shot from a scene in [[Leni Riefenstahl]]\u2019s ''[[Triumph of the Will]]'' (1935), specifically an outdoor rally for the [[Reichsarbeitsdienst]]. Other references to [[Nazism]] in the movie include the [[Uniforms of the German Army (1935\u20131945)|Wehrmacht-inspired uniforms]] and insignia of field grade officers, M.I.  working uniforms reminiscent of Mussolini's [[Blackshirts]], [[Albert Speer]]'s style of architecture, and its propagandistic dialogue (\"''Violence is the supreme authority!\"'').<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,290338,00.html|title=''Starship Troopers'' relys on Nazi imagery|last=Svetkey|first=Benjamin|date=November 21, 1997|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2014 interview on ''[[The Adam Carolla Show (podcast)|The Adam Carolla Show]]'', the actor [[Michael Ironside]], who read the novel as a youth, said that he asked Verhoeven, who grew up in [[Netherlands in World War II|Nazi-occupied Netherlands]], \"Why are you doing a right-wing fascist movie?\" Verhoeven replied, \"If I tell the world that a right-wing, fascist way of doing things doesn't work, no one will listen to me. So I'm going to make a perfect fascist world: everyone is beautiful, everything is shiny, everything has big guns and fancy ships, but it's only good for killing fucking Bugs!\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adamcarolla.com/michael-ironside-and-kristin-chenoweth/|title=Michael Ironside and Kristin Chenoweth|last=Laxamana|first=Chris|date=November 13, 2014|website=[[The Adam Carolla Show (podcast)|The Adam Carolla Show]]|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Themes==\nThe film includes visual allusions to [[propaganda film]]s such as ''[[Why We Fight]]'', ''[[Triumph of the Will]]'' and wartime [[newsreel]]s, and the symbols and certain clothing styles of the Federation are modeled on those of the Nazis (''e.g.'', [[windbreaker]]s, suits, caps, etc. Furthermore, the military intelligence officer's uniforms bear a striking similarity to those of the [[Allgemeine-SS]]).<ref name=\"gemsbok\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/a-decade-of-underrated-movies-1486|title=A Decade Of Underrated Movies: Who Will Love The Brown Bunny?|last=Tobias|first=Scott|date=October 19, 2005|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[Onion Inc.]]|accessdate=July 9, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.avclub.com/content/node/24776 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051201085900/http://avclub.com/content/node/24776 |url-status=dead |archivedate=2005-12-01 |title=Commentary Tracks Of The Blessed (1997 ''Starship Trooper'') |accessdate=2008-07-09 |date=2005-03-25 |publisher=A.V. Club }}</ref>\n\nThe use of Nazi imagery for the film's Americanized heroes (actually, Argentineans, etc.) occasioned comment. At the time of the film's theatrical release, the filmmakers did not explain their reasons for this choice. Some viewers interpreted it as a [[satire|satirical]] takedown of fascism, while others saw a celebration of it.<ref name=\"audiocommentary\">{{cite video |people=[[Paul Verhoeven|Verhoeven, Paul]] and [[Ed Neumeier|Neumeier, Ed]] |date=1997 |title=Audio Commentary for \"Starship Troopers\" |medium=DVD |publisher=[[Buena Vista International]]}}</ref>\n\nIn his DVD commentary, Verhoeven stated his intentions clearly: the film's message is that \"War makes fascists of us all\". He evoked Nazi Germany's fashion, iconography, and propaganda because he saw it as a natural evolution of the United States after [[World War II]], and especially after the [[Korean War]]. \"I've heard this film nicknamed ''[[All Quiet on the Western Front|All Quiet on the]]'' ''[[Star Trek|Final Frontier]]''\", he said, \"which is actually not far from the truth.\" Edward Neumeier broadly concurs, although he sees a satire on human history rather than solely the United States.<ref name=\"audiocommentary\"/> Verhoeven says his satirical use of irony and hyperbole is \"playing with [[fascism]] or fascist imagery to point out certain aspects of American society... of course, the movie is about 'Let's all go to war and let's all die.'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/paul-verhoeven,14078/|title=Interview: Paul Verhoeven|last=Tobias|first=Scott|date=April 3, 2007|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[Onion Inc.]]|accessdate=March 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nVerhoeven also compared the film to previous [[Monster movie|creature features]] from the 1950s, such as ''[[Them!]]'' (1954) and ''[[The Deadly Mantis]]'' (1957). Speaking about these films, he said they \"expressed the fear about the nuclear threat at the time and the feelings of helplessness and despair it caused\", while ''Starship Troopers'' (which was filmed in a post-[[Cold War]] United States) was about \"having no more enemies.\" He also discussed how making movies of the sort are difficult due to [[political correctness]], but \"if it's big insects that you can shoot to pieces, nobody cares.\" Tying this into the theme of the film, he said the statement of the film is that \"we like enemies.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yakir|first=Dan|date=February 1996|title=Starship Instincts|url=https://archive.org/details/starlog_magazine-223/page/n33|journal=[[Starlog]]|issue=223|pages=34\u201335|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nOn release, ''Starship Troopers'' received negative<!-- Do not change; this is supported by the source at the end of this sentence. --> reviews from American critics.<ref name=\"The Atlantic\"/>  In a 2017 retrospective round-up of the best films of 1997, ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' critic [[Ignatiy Vishnevetsky]] called the film \"too damn well-made for its own good\" and said that it confused audiences and critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/best-movies-1997-259214|title=The best movies of 1997|last=Vishnevetsky|first=Ignatiy|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=August 10, 2017|accessdate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> On [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], which collects both contemporaneous and modern reviews, it has a 62% approval rating based on 61 reviews, with a [[weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] of 6.07/10. The site's consensus is: \"A fun movie...if you can accept the excessive gore and wooden acting.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rottentomatoes.com/m/starship_troopers/|title=Starship Troopers (1997)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=|accessdate=June 29, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], it has a rating of 51/100 based on 20 reviews, indicating mixed or average reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/starship-troopers|title=Starship Troopers (1997)|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=March 22, 2013}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"C+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web |url=https://m.cinemascore.com |title=CinemaScore |work=cinemascore.com}}</ref>\n\nThe film was panned by [[Janet Maslin]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'', Jeff Vice of the ''[[Deseret News]]'', and [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', all of whom called it shallow and oriented toward teenage, male science fiction fans; Ebert had previously praised the satire in Verhoeven's ''[[RoboCop]]''.<ref name=\"The Atlantic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2013/11/-em-starship-troopers-em-one-of-the-most-misunderstood-movies-ever/281236/|title=''Starship Troopers'': One of the Most Misunderstood Movies Ever|last1=Marsh|first1=Calum|date=November 7, 2013|website=[[The Atlantic]]|url-status=live|accessdate=September 21, 2015}}</ref> Calum Marsh of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' disagreed with these critics in his 2013 article on the film, which he called a \"...satire, a ruthlessly funny and keenly self-aware sendup of right-wing militarism...[that] critiques the [[military\u2013industrial complex]], the jingoism of American foreign policy, and a culture that privileges reactionary violence over sensitivity and reason.\"<ref name=\"The Atlantic\"/> In a 2015 article for ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'', comedian and writer [[Aasif Mandvi]] criticized [[Casper Van Dien]]'s casting as [[whitewashing in film|whitewashing]] compared to the character's Filipino origins in the book.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/2012/05/14/whitewashing_a_history/slide_show/14|title=Whitewashing, a history|last=Mandvi|first=Aasif|date=May 13, 2012|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|accessdate=August 27, 2015|url-status=dead|authorlink=Aasif Mandvi}}</ref>{{Dead link|date=October 2019}}<!-- slide #14, a supplement to the article http://www.salon.com/2012/05/14/whitewashing_a_history/ -->\n\n''Starship Troopers'' was nominated for a number of awards in 1998, including the [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects]]; the film won [[Saturn Awards]] for Best Costumes and Best Special Effects at the 1998 Academy of Science Fiction, Fantasy and Horror Films, USA Awards.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}} It was also nominated for Worst Picture at the [[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards]] but lost to ''[[Batman and Robin (film)|Batman and Robin]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestinkers.com/1997.html|title=The Stinkers 1997 Ballot|publisher=[[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000818030700/http://www.thestinkers.com/1997.html|archive-date=August 18, 2000|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\n===Sequels===\nThe film has spawned four sequels, including two live-action films, ''[[Starship Troopers 2: Hero of the Federation]]'' (2004) and ''[[Starship Troopers 3: Marauder]]'' (2008), as well as two animated films, ''[[Starship Troopers: Invasion]]'' (2012) and ''[[Starship Troopers: Traitor of Mars]]'' (2017).\n\nThere was also a 1999 [[Spin-off (media)|spin off]] CGI animated half-hour television series entitled ''[[Roughnecks: Starship Troopers Chronicles]]'', which ran for eight story arcs and ended on an unresolved [[cliffhanger]].\n\n===Merchandise===\n{{Main|Starship Troopers#Influence|l1=Starship Troopers, influence}}\n\nIn 1997 [[Avalon Hill]] released ''[[Starship Troopers (board wargame)|Starship Troopers: Prepare for Battle!]]'', a board game based on the film version rather than Heinlein's book. Its gameplay focused on limited skirmishes rather than larger [[battle]]s. Avalon Hill had previously released a game called ''Robert Heinlein's Starship Troopers'' in 1976.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/tabletop/11532-8-Avalon-Hill-Board-Games-That-Deserve-New-Life.5|title=8 Avalon Hill Board Games That Deserve New Life|last=Keefer|first=John|date=May 30, 2014|website=[[Escapist Magazine]]|url-status=live|accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA [[real-time tactics]] [[video game]] titled ''[[Starship Troopers: Terran Ascendancy]]'' was released in 2000. This game also incorporated the powered suits in Heinlein's novel into the Verhoeven version of the Mobile Infantry. It was developed by Australian software company [[Blue Tongue Entertainment]].\n\nA [[first-person shooter]] game also titled ''[[Starship Troopers (video game)|Starship Troopers]]'' was released November 15, 2005. This version was developed by Strangelite Studios and published by [[Empire Interactive]]. Set five years after the events of the film, the game also featured Van Dien voicing the in-game version of Johnny Rico.\n\n[[Sega Pinball]] released a pinball machine based on the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipdb.org/machine.cgi?id=4341|title=Internet Pinball Machine Database: Sega 'Starship Troopers'|publisher=Internet Pinball Database|url-status=live|accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Proposed remake===\nIn December 2011, film producer [[Neal H. Moritz|Neal Moritz]] announced plans to [[Film remake|remake]] the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=32603|title=Starship Troopers Remake Planned|last1=White|first1=James|date=December 4, 2011|website=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]]|url-status=dead|accessdate=January 27, 2012}}</ref>{{Dead link|date=October 2019}} In November 2016, Columbia and Moritz announced the writing team of [[Mark Swift]] and [[Damian Shannon]] had been signed to pen the screenplay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/starship-troopers-reboot-works-943882|title='Starship Troopers' Reboot in the Works (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=November 3, 2016|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url-status=live|accessdate=June 7, 2017}}</ref> Verhoeven has expressed skepticism at the proposed remake, citing reports that it draws heavily from the original \"fascistic and militaristic\" 1959 novel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/starship-troopers-director-remake-fits-trump-presidency-w450823|title=Original 'Starship Troopers' Director: Remake Fits Trump Presidency|last1=Reed|first1=Ryan|date=November 16, 2016|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|url-status=live|accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of films featuring space stations]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0120201|Starship Troopers}}\n* {{Tcmdb title|328903|Starship Troopers}}\n* {{Amg movie|158876|Starship Troopers}}\n* {{AFI film|id=61484|title=Starship Troopers}}\n* {{mojo title|starshiptroopers|Starship Troopers}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|starship_troopers|Starship Troopers}}\n* {{metacritic film|starship-troopers|Starship Troopers}}\n\n{{Starship Troopers}}\n{{Paul Verhoeven}}\n\n[[Category:1997 films]]\n[[Category:1990s science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction adventure films]]\n[[Category:1990s satirical films]]\n[[Category:1990s science fiction adventure films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American satirical films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction war films]]\n[[Category:American splatter films]]\n[[Category:American teen films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on science fiction novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Paul Verhoeven]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Basil Poledouris]]\n[[Category:Films set in Buenos Aires]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 23rd century]]\n[[Category:Films set on fictional planets]]\n[[Category:Films shot in South Dakota]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Wyoming]]\n[[Category:Impact event films]]\n[[Category:War adventure films]]\n[[Category:Starship Troopers films]]\n[[Category:Touchstone Pictures films]]\n[[Category:TriStar Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = October 2019}}\n{{short description|1997 military science fiction movie directed by Paul Verhoeven}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Starship Troopers\n| image          = Starship Troopers - movie poster.jpg\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Paul Verhoeven]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jon Davison (film producer)|Jon Davison]]\n* [[Alan Marshall (producer)|Alan Marshall]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = [[Edward Neumeier]]\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Starship Troopers]]''|[[Robert A. Heinlein]]}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Casper Van Dien]]\n* [[Dina Meyer]]\n* [[Denise Richards]]\n* [[Jake Busey]]\n* [[Neil Patrick Harris]]\n* [[Patrick Muldoon]]\n* [[Michael Ironside]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Basil Poledouris]]\n| cinematography = [[Jost Vacano]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mark Goldblatt]]\n* Caroline Ross\n}}\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[TriStar Pictures]]\n* [[Touchstone Pictures]]\n* [[Jon Davison (film producer)|Jon Davison Productions]]\n}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Sony Pictures Releasing]] {{small|(North America)}}\n*[[Buena Vista International]] {{small|(International)}}\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|1997|11|07}}\n| runtime        = 129 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $105 million<ref name=\"boxofficemojo\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=starshiptroopers.htm|title=Starship Troopers|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref>\n| gross          = $121.2 million<ref name=\"boxofficemojo\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Starship Troopers''''' is a 1997 American [[Satire|satirical]] [[military science fiction]] [[action film]] directed by [[Paul Verhoeven]] and written by [[Edward Neumeier]]. It originally came from an unrelated script called ''Bug Hunt at Outpost Nine'',<ref name=\"Robley\">{{cite journal|last=Robley|first=Les Paul|date=November 1997|title=Interstellar Exterminators. Ornery insects threaten the galaxy in Starship Troopers|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1P3-1504299331/interstellar-exterminators|journal=[[American Cinematographer]]|publisher=[[American Society of Cinematographers]]|volume=78|issue=11|pages=56\u201366}}{{subscription required|via=[[Questia Online Library]]}}</ref> but eventually licensed the name ''[[Starship Troopers]]'' from the [[science fiction]] [[Starship Troopers|novel]] by [[Robert A. Heinlein]]. The story follows a young soldier named Johnny Rico and his exploits in the Mobile Infantry, a futuristic military unit. Rico's military career progresses from [[Army recruit|recruit]] to [[non-commissioned officer]] and finally to [[Officer (armed forces)|officer]] against the backdrop of an interstellar war between mankind and an insectoid species known as \"Arachnids\".\n\nThe only theatrically released film in the [[Starship Troopers (franchise)|''Starship Troopers'' film series]], it received mostly negative reviews from critics upon release<ref name=\"The Atlantic\"/> but has garnered a more mixed reception in retrospect. It grossed $54.5 million in the US and a total of $121.2 million worldwide against its budget of $105 million.<ref name=\"boxofficemojo\"/> The film was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects]] at the [[70th Academy Awards]] in 1998. In 2012, ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' ranked the film #20 on its list of the 100 Best Films of the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/feature/the-100-best-films-of-the-1990s/334/page_9|title=The 100 Best Films of the 1990s|date=November 5, 2012|website=[[Slant Magazine]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111231924/http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/feature/the-100-best-films-of-the-1990s/334/page_9|archive-date=November 11, 2012|accessdate=June 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Per [[WP:FILMPLOT]], film plots should be between 400 and 700 words. -->\nIn the 23rd century, while colonizing new planets, humans have encountered a hostile non-technological insectoid species known as Arachnids or \"[[Bug (Starship Troopers)|Bugs]]\".\n\nIn the United Citizen Federation, citizenship is earned by performing activities such as military service, which grants individuals opportunities prohibited to basic civilians. After graduating from high school in [[Buenos Aires]], [[Juan Rico|John \"Johnny\" Rico]], his girlfriend Carmen Iba\u00f1ez, and [[psychic]] best friend Carl Jenkins enlist in the Federal Service, despite Rico's parents' disapproval of military service. Carmen becomes a spaceship pilot, while Carl joins [[Military Intelligence]]. Rico enlists in the Mobile Infantry and is surprised to find Isabelle \"Dizzy\" Flores, his fellow ex-student, has deliberately transferred to his squad.\n\nIn Mobile Infantry basic training, Career Sgt Zim ruthlessly trains the recruits. Rico befriends fellow cadet Ace Levy and is later promoted to squad leader. He subsequently receives a [[Dear John letter]] from Carmen, as she desires a career with the fleet and now serves under Rico's high-school sports rival, Zander Barcalow. Following a [[Live fire exercise|live-fire training]] incident that kills one of Rico's squad members and causes another to quit out of guilt, Rico is demoted and [[Flagellation|flogged]]. He resigns and calls his parents to ask them if he can return home, but rescinds his resignation after an asteroid, reported to be launched by the Arachnids, obliterates Buenos Aires, killing his parents and millions of others.\n\nAn invasion force is deployed to [[Klendathu]], the Arachnids' home planet, but the operation severely underestimates the Arachnids and is a total disaster. Rico is severely wounded and mistakenly reported [[killed in action|KIA]]. After recovering, he, Ace, and Dizzy are reassigned to the \"Roughnecks\", an [[Special forces|elite unit]] commanded by Lt. Jean Rasczak, Rico's former high-school teacher. He quickly gains the respect of his peers and is promoted to the rank of Corporal after taking out a tanker bug. His relationship with Dizzy continues to grow, and they have sex during their night on Tango Urilla.\n\nThe Roughnecks respond to a distress call from Planet \"P\", where they reconnoiter an outpost that has been devastated by Bugs. They soon realize that the distress call is a trap, and the Arachnids swarm the outpost. Rico, now an acting sergeant, euthanizes a mortally wounded Rasczak after a buried Bug bites off his legs. Dizzy is killed, but the surviving Roughnecks are rescued by Carmen and Zander. Rico and Carmen encounter Carl, now a high-ranking intelligence officer, at Dizzy's funeral. Carl reveals that there is reason to believe an intelligent \"brain bug\" is directing the other Bugs and has been learning how to fight humans. He [[Battlefield promotion|field-promotes]] Rico to lieutenant and gives him command of the Roughnecks, ordering the Mobile Infantry units under his control to return to \"P\" in an attempt to capture the brain bug.\n\nThe Fleet encounters unexpected heavy fire from the Bugs and Carmen's ship is destroyed. Carmen and Zander's escape pod crashes into a Bug tunnel system near Rico. They are surrounded by Bugs and a brain bug uses its [[proboscis]] to pierce Zander's skull and eat his brain. As it is about to do the same to Carmen, she cuts off its proboscis with a knife. Rico, Watkins and Ace arrive and threaten the Bugs with a small [[Tactical nuclear weapon|nuclear bomb]], which the brain bug recognizes. They flee while the brain bug makes its escape. Arachnids pursue them and Watkins, mortally wounded, sacrifices himself by detonating the bomb to enable the others to escape.\n\nAfter returning to the surface, they find that former Sergeant Zim, who had requested a demotion to private so that he could serve at the front, has captured the brain bug. Carl tells Rico and Carmen that the humans will soon be victorious now that Military Intelligence can study the brain bug. Carl mentally scans the Bug and reveals that it is afraid, to the cheers of the troops. A [[propaganda]] clip shows Carmen, Ace, and Rico as model servicemen, encouraging viewers to enlist in the armed forces.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=27em}}\n* [[Casper Van Dien]] as [[John Rico|Pvt./Cpl./Sgt./Lt. John \"Johnny\" Rico]]\n* [[Dina Meyer]] as Pvt. Isabelle \"Dizzy\" Flores\n* [[Denise Richards]] as Lt./Capt. Carmen Iba\u00f1ez\n* [[Jake Busey]] as Pvt. Ace Levy\n* [[Neil Patrick Harris]] as Col. Carl Jenkins\n* [[Patrick Muldoon]] as Lt. Zander Barcalow\n* [[Clancy Brown]] as Career Sgt./Pvt. Zim\n* [[Michael Ironside]] as Lt. Jean Rasczak\n* [[Seth Gilliam]] as Cpl. Sugar Watkins\n* [[Bruce Gray]] as Sky Marshal Dienes\n* [[Marshall Bell]] as General Owen\n* [[Eric Bruskotter]] as Private Breckinridge\n* [[Brenda Strong]] as Captain Deladier\n* [[Christopher Curry (actor)|Christopher Curry]] as Bill Rico\n* [[Lenore Kasdorf]] as Mrs. Rico\n* Denise Dowse as Sky Marshal Meru\n* [[Amy Smart]] as Pilot Cadet/Lt. Lumbreiser\n* [[Dean Norris]] as Commanding officer\n* [[Rue McClanahan]] as Biology teacher\n* [[Dale Dye]] as Unnamed general\n* [[Anthony Ruivivar]] as Shujumi\n* [[Robert David Hall]] as [[Recruiter]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Background==\n\n===Production===\n[[Image:HellsHalfAcre.JPG|thumb|right|Badlands of [[Hell's Half Acre (Wyoming)|Hell's Half Acre]], Natrona County, Wyoming, where parts of ''Starship Troopers'' were filmed.]]\nThe film started life as a script called ''Bug Hunt at Outpost Nine''.<ref name=\"Robley\"/> When similarities, especially the \"bugs\", were pointed out between this and the novel ''[[Starship Troopers]]'', plans were made to license the rights to the book and tweak character names and circumstances to match. [[Paul Verhoeven]] had never read the book, and attempted to read it for the film, but it made him \"bored and depressed\", so he read only a few chapters:\n\n<blockquote>I stopped after two chapters because it was so boring \u2026 It is really quite a bad book. I asked [[Edward Neumeier|Ed Neumeier]] to tell me the story because I just couldn't read the thing. It's a very right-wing book.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/paul-verhoeven/|title=Triple Dutch: Paul Verhoeven's sci-fi trilogy|last1=Smith|first1=Adam|last2=Williams|first2=Owen|date=February 12, 2015|website=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|url-status=dead|accessdate=December 7, 2016|quote=I stopped after two chapters because it was so boring,\" says Verhoeven of his attempts to read Heinlein's opus. \"It is really quite a bad book. I asked Ed Neumeier to tell me the story because I just couldn't read the thing. It's a very right-wing book. And with the movie we tried, and I think at least partially succeeded, in commenting on that at the same time. It would be eat your cake and have it. All the way through we were fighting with the fascism, the ultra-militarism. All the way through I wanted the audience to be asking, 'Are these people crazy?'}}</ref>{{Dead link|date=October 2019}}</blockquote>\n\nNeumeier had previously worked with Verhoeven as a writer on ''[[RoboCop|Robocop]]'' (1987).\n\nThe \"bug planet\" scenes were filmed in the [[badlands]] of [[Hell's Half Acre (Wyoming)|Hell's Half Acre]] in [[Natrona County]], Wyoming.<ref name=\"audiocommentary\" />\n\nTwo nude scenes were kept in the original version (the co-ed shower and a bedroom romp between Rico and Dizzy), although these were modified in the broadcast version. The cast agreed to do the co-ed shower scene only if Verhoeven agreed to direct the scene naked, which he did.<ref name=\"audiocommentary\"/>\n\nIn the [[audio commentary]] on the DVD or Blu-ray release, Verhoeven remarks that he had hoped to cast actors whose age more closely matched that of the characters\u2014and indeed of real-world soldiers\u2014but that the producers felt such actors would look too young. The teacher and leader of the \"Roughnecks\" in the novel are combined into one role played by Ironside.<ref name=\"audiocommentary\"/>\n\nTest audience reactions led to several minor changes before the film was released. Originally, it was clear that Carmen was torn between Rico and Zander. Test audiences, regardless of gender, strongly felt that a woman could not love two men at once, so scenes which portrayed this were cut. These audiences also felt it was immoral for Carmen to choose a career ahead of being loyal to Rico, to the extent that many commented that, in so doing, Carmen should have been the one to die instead of Dizzy. While admitting it may have been a bad commercial decision not to change the film to accommodate this, the producer and director did cut a scene from after Zander's death in which Carmen and Rico kiss, which the audience believed made the previous betrayal even more immoral.<ref name=\"audiocommentary\"/>\n\n===Relationship to novel===\nBecause the film originated from an unrelated script, with names and superficial details from the [[Starship Troopers|novel]] being added retroactively, there are many differences between the two.<ref name=\"gemsbok\">{{Cite web|url=http://thegemsbok.com/art-reviews-and-articles/thursday-theater-starship-troopers-paul-verhoeven-robert-heinlein/|title=Poking Fun at Militarism: How Paul Verhoeven\u2019s Cult Classic ''Starship Troopers'' Willfully Discards Robert Heinlein\u2019s Novel|last=Podgorski|first=Daniel|date=February 4, 2016|website=The Gemsbok|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref> While the novel has [[Starship Troopers#Controversy|been accused of]] promoting militarism, fascism, and military rule,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/2.10/godwin.if.html|title=Meme, Counter-meme|last=Godwin|first=Mike|date=October 1, 1994|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nitrosyncretic.com/pdfs/nature_of_fedsvc_1996.pdf|title=The Nature of \"Federal Service\" in Robert A. Heinlein\u2019s ''Starship Troopers''|last=Gifford|first=James|date=|year=2011|website=Nitrosyncretic Press|publisher=|orig-year=1986|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref> the film satirizes these concepts by featuring bombastic displays of nationalism as well as news reports that are intensely [[xenophobia|xenophobic]] and [[propaganda|propagandistic]].<ref name=\"gemsbok\"/>\n\nVerhoeven stated in 1997 that the first scene of the film\u2014an advertisement for the Mobile Infantry\u2014was adapted shot-for-shot from a scene in [[Leni Riefenstahl]]\u2019s ''[[Triumph of the Will]]'' (1935), specifically an outdoor rally for the [[Reichsarbeitsdienst]]. Other references to [[Nazism]] in the movie include the [[Uniforms of the German Army (1935\u20131945)|Wehrmacht-inspired uniforms]] and insignia of field grade officers, M.I.  working uniforms reminiscent of Mussolini's [[Blackshirts]], [[Albert Speer]]'s style of architecture, and its propagandistic dialogue (\"''Violence is the supreme authority!\"'').<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,290338,00.html|title=''Starship Troopers'' relys on Nazi imagery|last=Svetkey|first=Benjamin|date=November 21, 1997|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2014 interview on ''[[The Adam Carolla Show (podcast)|The Adam Carolla Show]]'', the actor [[Michael Ironside]], who read the novel as a youth, said that he asked Verhoeven, who grew up in [[Netherlands in World War II|Nazi-occupied Netherlands]], \"Why are you doing a right-wing fascist movie?\" Verhoeven replied, \"If I tell the world that a right-wing, fascist way of doing things doesn't work, no one will listen to me. So I'm going to make a perfect fascist world: everyone is beautiful, everything is shiny, everything has big guns and fancy ships, but it's only good for killing fucking Bugs!\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adamcarolla.com/michael-ironside-and-kristin-chenoweth/|title=Michael Ironside and Kristin Chenoweth|last=Laxamana|first=Chris|date=November 13, 2014|website=[[The Adam Carolla Show (podcast)|The Adam Carolla Show]]|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Themes==\nThe film includes visual allusions to [[propaganda film]]s such as ''[[Why We Fight]]'', ''[[Triumph of the Will]]'' and wartime [[newsreel]]s, and the symbols and certain clothing styles of the Federation are modeled on those of the Nazis (''e.g.'', [[windbreaker]]s, suits, caps, etc. Furthermore, the military intelligence officer's uniforms bear a striking similarity to those of the [[Allgemeine-SS]]).<ref name=\"gemsbok\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/a-decade-of-underrated-movies-1486|title=A Decade Of Underrated Movies: Who Will Love The Brown Bunny?|last=Tobias|first=Scott|date=October 19, 2005|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[Onion Inc.]]|accessdate=July 9, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.avclub.com/content/node/24776 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051201085900/http://avclub.com/content/node/24776 |url-status=dead |archivedate=2005-12-01 |title=Commentary Tracks Of The Blessed (1997 ''Starship Trooper'') |accessdate=2008-07-09 |date=2005-03-25 |publisher=A.V. Club }}</ref>\n\nThe use of Nazi imagery for the film's Americanized heroes (actually, Argentineans, etc.) occasioned comment. At the time of the film's theatrical release, the filmmakers did not explain their reasons for this choice. Some viewers interpreted it as a [[satire|satirical]] takedown of fascism, while others saw a celebration of it.<ref name=\"audiocommentary\">{{cite video |people=[[Paul Verhoeven|Verhoeven, Paul]] and [[Ed Neumeier|Neumeier, Ed]] |date=1997 |title=Audio Commentary for \"Starship Troopers\" |medium=DVD |publisher=[[Buena Vista International]]}}</ref>\n\nIn his DVD commentary, Verhoeven stated his intentions clearly: the film's message is that \"War makes fascists of us all\". He evoked Nazi Germany's fashion, iconography, and propaganda because he saw it as a natural evolution of the United States after [[World War II]], and especially after the [[Korean War]]. \"I've heard this film nicknamed ''[[All Quiet on the Western Front|All Quiet on the]]'' ''[[Star Trek|Final Frontier]]''\", he said, \"which is actually not far from the truth.\" Edward Neumeier broadly concurs, although he sees a satire on human history rather than solely the United States.<ref name=\"audiocommentary\"/> Verhoeven says his satirical use of irony and hyperbole is \"playing with [[fascism]] or fascist imagery to point out certain aspects of American society... of course, the movie is about 'Let's all go to war and let's all die.'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/paul-verhoeven,14078/|title=Interview: Paul Verhoeven|last=Tobias|first=Scott|date=April 3, 2007|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[Onion Inc.]]|accessdate=March 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nVerhoeven also compared the film to previous [[Monster movie|creature features]] from the 1950s, such as ''[[Them!]]'' (1954) and ''[[The Deadly Mantis]]'' (1957). Speaking about these films, he said they \"expressed the fear about the nuclear threat at the time and the feelings of helplessness and despair it caused\", while ''Starship Troopers'' (which was filmed in a post-[[Cold War]] United States) was about \"having no more enemies.\" He also discussed how making movies of the sort are difficult due to [[political correctness]], but \"if it's big insects that you can shoot to pieces, nobody cares.\" Tying this into the theme of the film, he said the statement of the film is that \"we like enemies.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yakir|first=Dan|date=February 1996|title=Starship Instincts|url=https://archive.org/details/starlog_magazine-223/page/n33|journal=[[Starlog]]|issue=223|pages=34\u201335|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nOn release, ''Starship Troopers'' received negative<!-- Do not change; this is supported by the source at the end of this sentence. --> reviews from American critics.<ref name=\"The Atlantic\"/>  In a 2017 retrospective round-up of the best films of 1997, ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' critic [[Ignatiy Vishnevetsky]] called the film \"too damn well-made for its own good\" and said that it confused audiences and critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/best-movies-1997-259214|title=The best movies of 1997|last=Vishnevetsky|first=Ignatiy|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=August 10, 2017|accessdate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> On [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], which collects both contemporaneous and modern reviews, it has a 62% approval rating based on 61 reviews, with a [[weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] of 6.07/10. The site's consensus is: \"A fun movie...if you can accept the excessive gore and wooden acting.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rottentomatoes.com/m/starship_troopers/|title=Starship Troopers (1997)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=|accessdate=June 29, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], it has a rating of 51/100 based on 20 reviews, indicating mixed or average reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/starship-troopers|title=Starship Troopers (1997)|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=March 22, 2013}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"C+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web |url=https://m.cinemascore.com |title=CinemaScore |work=cinemascore.com}}</ref>\n\nThe film was panned by [[Janet Maslin]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'', Jeff Vice of the ''[[Deseret News]]'', and [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', all of whom called it shallow and oriented toward teenage, male science fiction fans; Ebert had previously praised the satire in Verhoeven's ''[[RoboCop]]''.<ref name=\"The Atlantic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2013/11/-em-starship-troopers-em-one-of-the-most-misunderstood-movies-ever/281236/|title=''Starship Troopers'': One of the Most Misunderstood Movies Ever|last1=Marsh|first1=Calum|date=November 7, 2013|website=[[The Atlantic]]|url-status=live|accessdate=September 21, 2015}}</ref> Calum Marsh of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' disagreed with these critics in his 2013 article on the film, which he called a \"...satire, a ruthlessly funny and keenly self-aware sendup of right-wing militarism...[that] critiques the [[military\u2013industrial complex]], the jingoism of American foreign policy, and a culture that privileges reactionary violence over sensitivity and reason.\"<ref name=\"The Atlantic\"/> In a 2015 article for ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'', comedian and writer [[Aasif Mandvi]] criticized [[Casper Van Dien]]'s casting as [[whitewashing in film|whitewashing]] compared to the character's Filipino origins in the book.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/2012/05/14/whitewashing_a_history/slide_show/14|title=Whitewashing, a history|last=Mandvi|first=Aasif|date=May 13, 2012|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|accessdate=August 27, 2015|url-status=dead|authorlink=Aasif Mandvi}}</ref>{{Dead link|date=October 2019}}<!-- slide #14, a supplement to the article http://www.salon.com/2012/05/14/whitewashing_a_history/ -->\n\n''Starship Troopers'' was nominated for a number of awards in 1998, including the [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects]]; the film won [[Saturn Awards]] for Best Costumes and Best Special Effects at the 1998 Academy of Science Fiction, Fantasy and Horror Films, USA Awards.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}} It was also nominated for Worst Picture at the [[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards]] but lost to ''[[Batman and Robin (film)|Batman and Robin]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestinkers.com/1997.html|title=The Stinkers 1997 Ballot|publisher=[[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000818030700/http://www.thestinkers.com/1997.html|archive-date=August 18, 2000|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\n===Sequels===\nThe film has spawned four sequels, including two live-action films, ''[[Starship Troopers 2: Hero of the Federation]]'' (2004) and ''[[Starship Troopers 3: Marauder]]'' (2008), as well as two animated films, ''[[Starship Troopers: Invasion]]'' (2012) and ''[[Starship Troopers: Traitor of Mars]]'' (2017).\n\nThere was also a 1999 [[Spin-off (media)|spin off]] CGI animated half-hour television series entitled ''[[Roughnecks: Starship Troopers Chronicles]]'', which ran for eight story arcs and ended on an unresolved [[cliffhanger]].\n\n===Merchandise===\n{{Main|Starship Troopers#Influence|l1=Starship Troopers, influence}}\n\nIn 1997 [[Avalon Hill]] released ''[[Starship Troopers (board wargame)|Starship Troopers: Prepare for Battle!]]'', a board game based on the film version rather than Heinlein's book. Its gameplay focused on limited skirmishes rather than larger [[battle]]s. Avalon Hill had previously released a game called ''Robert Heinlein's Starship Troopers'' in 1976.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/tabletop/11532-8-Avalon-Hill-Board-Games-That-Deserve-New-Life.5|title=8 Avalon Hill Board Games That Deserve New Life|last=Keefer|first=John|date=May 30, 2014|website=[[Escapist Magazine]]|url-status=live|accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA [[real-time tactics]] [[video game]] titled ''[[Starship Troopers: Terran Ascendancy]]'' was released in 2000. This game also incorporated the powered suits in Heinlein's novel into the Verhoeven version of the Mobile Infantry. It was developed by Australian software company [[Blue Tongue Entertainment]].\n\nA [[first-person shooter]] game also titled ''[[Starship Troopers (video game)|Starship Troopers]]'' was released November 15, 2005. This version was developed by Strangelite Studios and published by [[Empire Interactive]]. Set five years after the events of the film, the game also featured Van Dien voicing the in-game version of Johnny Rico.\n\n[[Sega Pinball]] released a pinball machine based on the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipdb.org/machine.cgi?id=4341|title=Internet Pinball Machine Database: Sega 'Starship Troopers'|publisher=Internet Pinball Database|url-status=live|accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Proposed remake===\nIn December 2011, film producer [[Neal H. Moritz|Neal Moritz]] announced plans to [[Film remake|remake]] the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=32603|title=Starship Troopers Remake Planned|last1=White|first1=James|date=December 4, 2011|website=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]]|url-status=dead|accessdate=January 27, 2012}}</ref>{{Dead link|date=October 2019}} In November 2016, Columbia and Moritz announced the writing team of [[Mark Swift]] and [[Damian Shannon]] had been signed to pen the screenplay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/starship-troopers-reboot-works-943882|title='Starship Troopers' Reboot in the Works (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=November 3, 2016|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url-status=live|accessdate=June 7, 2017}}</ref> Verhoeven has expressed skepticism at the proposed remake, citing reports that it draws heavily from the original \"fascistic and militaristic\" 1959 novel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/starship-troopers-director-remake-fits-trump-presidency-w450823|title=Original 'Starship Troopers' Director: Remake Fits Trump Presidency|last1=Reed|first1=Ryan|date=November 16, 2016|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|url-status=live|accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of films featuring space stations]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0120201|Starship Troopers}}\n* {{Tcmdb title|328903|Starship Troopers}}\n* {{Amg movie|158876|Starship Troopers}}\n* {{AFI film|id=61484|title=Starship Troopers}}\n* {{mojo title|starshiptroopers|Starship Troopers}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|starship_troopers|Starship Troopers}}\n* {{metacritic film|starship-troopers|Starship Troopers}}\n\n{{Starship Troopers}}\n{{Paul Verhoeven}}\n\n[[Category:1997 films]]\n[[Category:1990s science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction adventure films]]\n[[Category:1990s satirical films]]\n[[Category:1990s science fiction adventure films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American satirical films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction war films]]\n[[Category:American splatter films]]\n[[Category:American teen films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on science fiction novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Paul Verhoeven]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Basil Poledouris]]\n[[Category:Films set in Buenos Aires]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 23rd century]]\n[[Category:Films set on fictional planets]]\n[[Category:Films shot in South Dakota]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Wyoming]]\n[[Category:Impact event films]]\n[[Category:War adventure films]]\n[[Category:Starship Troopers films]]\n[[Category:Touchstone Pictures films]]\n[[Category:TriStar Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "73.189.205.163", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePlot)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Starship_Troopers_(film)"}
{"title_page": "History of the FA Cup", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\nThe '''history of the [[FA Cup]]''' in association football dates back to [[1871\u201372 FA Cup|1871\u201372]]. Aside from suspensions during the [[First World War|First]] and [[Second World War]]s, the competition has been played every year since.\n\n==History==\n\n===19th century===\n[[File:1stRoyalEngineers.png|thumb|right|The [[Royal Engineers A.F.C.|Royal Engineers]] squad that played the first [[FA Cup]] final in [[1872 FA Cup Final|1872]]]]\nOn 20 July 1871, in the offices of [[The Sportsman (1865 newspaper)|''The Sportsman'' newspaper]], [[C. W. Alcock]] proposed to [[The Football Association]] committee that \"it is desirable that a Challenge Cup should be established in connection with the Association for which all clubs belonging to the Association should be invited to compete\". The other committee members were:<ref>{{cite book |title= The Complete Record of the FA Cup|last= Collett|first= Mike |year= 2003|publisher= Sports Books|isbn=1-899807-19-5|pages=16\u201317}}</ref>\n* [[Alfred Stair|A. Stair]] (F.A. Treasurer) ([[Upton Park F.C.|Upton Park]])\n* [[Charles W. Stephenson|C.W. Stephenson]] ([[Westminster School]])\n* J.H. Gifford ([[Civil Service F.C.|Civil Service]])\n* D. Allport ([[Crystal Palace F.C. (1861)|Crystal Palace]])\n* [[Morton Betts|M.P. Betts]] ([[Harrow School]])\n* Capt. [[Francis Marindin]] ([[Royal Engineers F.C.|Royal Engineers]])\n\nThe proposition was carried.\n\nThe [[1871\u201372 FA Cup|inaugural FA Cup tournament]] kicked off in November 1871. After thirteen games in all, [[Wanderers F.C.|Wanderers]] were crowned the winners in the final at [[Kennington Oval]], on 16 March 1872.{{sfn|Barber|1981|p=1871\u20132}} The following year, Wanderers retained the title after receiving a bye to the final, the 'Challenge Round', where they beat [[Oxford University A.F.C.|Oxford University]] to retain the Cup. The rules were changed for the following season, to help inspire teams to try to get to the final, instead of knowing who their opponents would be before they reached it.{{fact|date=December 2016}}\n\n1875 saw the first final to be replayed, between Royal Engineers and [[Old Etonians F.C.|Old Etonians]], on Saturday 13 March (score 1-1 after extra time, in the first drawn final) and on Tuesday 16 March (score 2-0 between the respective teams), both times at [[Kennington Oval]].\n\nThe modern cup was beginning to be established by the 1888\u201389 season, when qualifying rounds were introduced, with clubs competing on regional basis until only one was left for the Fourth Qualifying Round, and in the same season, the 'magic of the cup' began when Warwick County became the first non-league side to beat a First Division club on 6 October 1888, winning 2\u20131 away at [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]].<ref name=\"Collett 2003 878\">{{cite book |last= Collett |first= Mike |title= The Complete Record of The FA Cup |year= 2003 |isbn= 1-899807-19-5 |pages=878}}</ref>\n\n===20th century===\n[[File:Facupfinal1901-A.jpg|thumb|1901 FA Cup final at Crystal Palace, Sandy Brown just scored a goal]] \nThe [[1901 FA Cup Final]] was won by London club [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], which became the only [[non-League football|non-League]] club to have ever won the FA Cup final after the formation of the [[Football League]] in 1888 (Tottenham were then in the [[Southern Football League|Southern League]]). The final between Tottenham and [[Sheffield United]] held at [[Crystal_Palace_National_Sports_Centre#Crystal_Palace_FA_Cup_ Finals_1895.E2.80.931914|Crystal Palace]] was attended by 110,820 fans, then the largest crowd ever for a football match.<ref name=\"turf 2\">{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=l67VDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT29&lpg=PT29#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Turf Wars: A History of London Football |first= Steve|last= Tongue |chapter=Chapter 2: Taking Shape (1901-1920)|publisher= Pitch Publishing|isbn=9781785312489  }}</ref>  The game ended in a 2\u20132 draw, with both Spurs goals from [[Sandy Brown (footballer born 1879)|Sandy Brown]], and a disputed goal from Sheffield \u2013 the final was the first to be filmed and it would be the first referee decision demonstrated to be wrong by film footage as it showed that the ball did not cross the line.<ref name=\"turf 2\"/><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S07SDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT11&lpg=PT11#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=People's History of Tottenham Hotspur: How Spurs Fans Shaped the Identity of One of the World\u2019s Most Famous Clubs|authors= Martin Cloake, Alan Fisher |publisher= Pitch Publishing |date=15 August 2016 |chapter=Introduction}}</ref> The replay was held at [[Burnden Park]], Bolton on 27 April 1901, which Spurs won 3\u20131. \n\nIn the [[1915 FA Cup Final|1915 final]], [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] beat [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] 3\u20130 at [[Old Trafford (football ground)|Old Trafford]]. The final became known as \"The Khaki Cup Final\" owing to the large number of uniformed soldiers in attendance. This year the FA Cup competition was controversial as the [[First World War]] had started, and concerns were raised about the appropriateness of football competition continuing in the midst of a world war. The Football Association however argued that it would be better to carry on to provide relief for the workers and soldiers.{{sfn|Barber|1981|p=1914\u20135}} In the following year the competition was suspended.\n\nThe [[1923 FA Cup Final|1923 final]] was the first FA Cup final to be played at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]], which was known at the time as the Empire Stadium. Over 200,000 people squeezed into a stadium meant for 127,000 and many spilt out onto the pitch. It took three-quarter of an hour for mounted police to clear the field before the game could start. [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] beat [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]] 2\u20130 in the match.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s9ak2PkMzDwC&pg=PA89#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Now You Know Soccer|first= Doug |last=Lennox |publisher= Dundurn |date=1 June 2009 |isbn= 9781770706132}}</ref> \n\nThe practice of teams from the top two divisions receiving exemption to the Third Round of the competition began in the 1925/26 season.{{fact|date=December 2016}} The [[1926 FA Cup Final|1926 final]] is the first to be played under a change to the offside rule.{{sfn|Barber|1981|p=1925\u20136}}\n\nThe [[1945\u201346 in English football|1945\u20131946]] FA Cup was the first played since the competition was suspended during [[World War II]]. For one season only, as the intermediate [[Football League North and South|Football League North and Football League South]] were of variable quality, to boost clubs' income each tie was played over two legs (one home, one away with the scores being added together to decide who went through) to increase the number of matches in the season. Matches that were level at the end of both legs were replayed at the stadium of whichever team had played the second leg away. The final, played at a neutral venue, remained a single match affair, decided by extra time if teams were level after 90 minutes. The final was won by [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] 4\u20131.{{sfn|Barber|1981|p=1945\u20136}}\n\nIn the [[1966\u201367 FA Cup]] the first substitutes were allowed after many years of finals proving unbalanced due to injuries which forced players into leaving the field early. Players had suffered broken bones in the 1957, 1959, 1960, 1961 and 1965 finals. They were not, however, used in the final until the next year in the [[1968 FA Cup Final]], when [[Dennis Clarke]] replaced [[John Kaye (footballer)|John Kaye]] for West Bromwich Albion.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/when-saturday-comes-blog/2015/sep/18/fifty-years-substitutions-football-sport |title=Fifty years of substitutions in football: from necessary novelties to tactical tools |first=Peter |last=Bateman |work=The Guardian |date=18 September 2015 }}</ref>\n\n1970 saw the first Wembley final to go to a replay. The replayed final was played at [[Old Trafford (football ground)|Old Trafford]] due to the damaged state of the Wembley pitch caused by the Horse of the Year Show and was contested between [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]]. 1970 also saw the first [[FA Cup Third-fourth place matches|third place play-off]] with Manchester United beating Watford 2\u20130. This play-off proved short-lived, and the 1973\u201374 competition saw the last 3rd place play-off match, contested by [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] and [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]], with Burnley winning 1\u20130 at [[Filbert Street]].<ref name=\"complete1\">{{cite book |last= Collett |first= Mike |title= The Complete Record of The FA Cup |year= 2003 |isbn= 1-899807-19-5 |pages=795}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1972 FA Cup Final|1972]] the FA Cup celebrated its centenary (though this was not its 100th season, due to interruptions for the two world wars). [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] won the final against holders [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. The [[1973 FA Cup Final]] was the 50th anniversary of Wembley as a venue for the cup final.{{fact|date=December 2016}}\n\n[[File:Ardiles villa fa cup.jpg|thumb|left|170px|[[Osvaldo Ardiles]] and [[Ricardo Villa]] holding the FA Cup trophy won in [[1981 FA Cup Final|1981]]]]\nIn 1981, The [[1981 FA Cup Final|100th FA Cup final]] took place between Tottenham Hotspur and [[Manchester City]].  It finished 1\u20131 after extra time.  For the first time, the replay was held again at Wembley \u2013 previously replayed finals had been held at other neutral grounds. Tottenham won 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29476689 |title=Top 50 FA Cup goals: 'And still Ricky Villa |work=BBC Sport |date=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1990\u201391 FA Cup]], the [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] v [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] fourth round tie had to be replayed three times. After the third replay, The FA decided that from the first round onwards, one replay, then extra time, then a penalty shootout would be a suitable alternative to a fixtures backlog.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/cup-marathon-which-saw-the-fa-blow-whistle-on-multiple-replays-1-7707317 |title=Cup marathon which saw the FA blow whistle on multiple replays|work=Yorkshire Post |date=1 February 2016}}</ref> The semi-final of this year was the first to be played at Wembley, with Tottenham beating Arsenal 3\u20131, including a 30-yard free kick from [[Paul Gascoigne]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/1216438.stm|title=FA Cup revisited: Spurs v Arsenal |work=BBC Sport |date= 5 April 2001}}</ref>\n\nAfter the change in replay rule starting with the season [[1991\u201392 FA Cup]] where multiple replays were replaced by one replay and penalty kicks after extra time, the first penalty takers in the competition proper were [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] and [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]], with Rotherham winning 7\u20136 in a first round replay. In the qualifying rounds, multiple replays lasted until 1996/97, with the game between Morecambe and Lancaster City on 4 November 1996 being the last second replay.<ref>[http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/FACompetitions/TheFACup/Archive.aspx 1996\u20131997 competition results, FA.com]</ref>\n\nIn 1993, both semi-finals were played at Wembley Stadium for the first time ever, one between Arsenal and Tottenham, the other between Sheffield Wednesday and Sheffield United. In 1993, the last ever FA Cup final replay took place, with [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] beating [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] 2\u20131. Arsenal became the first team to win both the FA Cup and the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] in the same season, beating Sheffield Wednesday in both finals, the first time the same teams contested the two cup finals in the same season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/chris-waddle-no-one-remembers-1993-league-cup-final-it-was-rubbish |title=Chris Waddle: No one remembers the 1993 League Cup Final \u2013 it was Rubbish |author=Chris Flanagan|date=26 October 2015 |work=FourFourTwo}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, the last ever FA Cup semi-final replay took place. From 2000 onwards, it was decided that any semi-finals and finals would go first to extra time then penalties, rather than be replayed.{{fact|date=December 2016}} In 1999, under pressure from [[The Football Association|The FA]], Manchester United became the first FA Cup holders not to defend their title when they withdrew from the FA Cup, instead electing to take part in the inaugural [[FIFA Club World Championship]] played in Brazil. To decide who took their place, a \"lucky losers\" draw was held containing the 20 teams knocked out in the second round; [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] were selected.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/sport/football/fa_cup/544737.stm |title=Lucky Darlington land Villa trip |date=1 December 1999 |work=BBC}}</ref>\n\n===21st century===\n[[File:Cfc fa cup2007.jpg|thumb|First [[2007 FA Cup Final|FA Cup Final]] at the new Wembley Stadium in 2007]]\nRedevelopment of Wembley saw the final played outside of England for the first time ever, with the 2001\u20132006 finals being played at the [[Millennium Stadium]] in [[Cardiff]].{{fact|date=December 2016}}\n\nUpon the opening of the new [[Wembley Stadium]], the Final returned to Wembley, but the semi-finals were played at neutral grounds. However, in 2003, it was announced that all future semi-finals would be played at the new Wembley Stadium once it had opened, and this took effect in 2008.{{fact|date=December 2016}}\n\nBeginning with the [[2016\u201317 FA Cup|2016\u201317 competition]], all quarter-final matches will be played to a result on the day (with draws followed by extra time, with a penalty shootout if level after extra time) instead of being replayed in the event of a draw.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.thefa.com/news/the-fa-cup/2016/may/quarter-final-sudden-death-replays |title=No replays in the 2017 Emirates FA Cup quarter-finals |publisher=The Football Association |date=26 May 2016 |accessdate=25 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Broadcasting===\nThe 1927 final was the first ever Cup Final to be broadcast by the [[BBC Radio|BBC]], who produced a numbered grid of the pitch for Radio Times readers to follow the ball. This gave rise to the popular myth of the origin of the phrase, \"[[wikt:back to square one|Back to square one]]\" (i.e. a back-pass to the goalkeeper).{{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}\n\nIn 1938, after 29 minutes of extra time, it was still 0\u20130 between [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston]] and [[Huddersfield Town F.C.|Huddersfield]]. [[BBC Radio]] commentator [[Thomas Woodrooffe]] declared: \"If there's a goal scored now, I'll eat my hat.\" Seconds later Preston was awarded a penalty from which [[George Mutch]] scored. Woodrooffe kept his promise. This was also the first FA Cup Final to be broadcast live by BBC Television.{{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}\n\n==Notable events==\n\n===Inaugural tournament===\nThe [[1871\u201372 FA Cup|inaugural FA Cup tournament]] kicked off in November 1871. Four first-round matches were the first FA Cup games ever played \u2013 on 11 November 1871. The first Cup goal was scored by [[Clapham Rovers F.C.|Clapham Rovers]] player [[Jarvis Kenrick]] in a 3\u20130 win over Upton Park (Kenrick scoring twice in the process). The following year, on 16 March 1872, [[Wanderers F.C.|Wanderers]] became the first winners of the FA Cup, beating [[Royal Engineers A.F.C.|Royal Engineers]] 1\u20130 at [[The Oval]]. Fifteen clubs had entered, only twelve actually played, and there were thirteen games in total. The winning goal was scored by [[Morton Peto Betts]], who played under the pseudonym of 'A.H. Chequer'.\n\n===White Horse Final===\n[[File:White Horse Final1923.jpg|right|thumb|The first FA Cup Final at Wembley in 1923, the crowd at the Cup Final was so large that fans swarmed onto the pitch]]\n\nThe first Wembley FA Cup Final, played on 28 April 1923, was marked by disorderly scenes unparalleled in the history of football. Before the match a massive crowd outside the stadium rushed the gates, burst the barriers and swarmed on to the pitch. Kick-off was delayed for 45 minutes as mounted police, with PC [[George Scorey]] on his white charger \"Billy\" \u2013 hence the [[FA Cup Final 1923|\"White Horse Final\"]] \u2013 particularly visible, encouraged people to move behind the touchlines. [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton]] beat West Ham 2\u20130 and the first Wembley goal was scored after just two minutes by David Jack. It was estimated that 200,000 fans had squeezed into Wembley and Cup Finals were made \"all ticket\" after that.\n\n===Burnden Park disaster===\nDuring a Sixth Round second-leg tie between Bolton and Stoke City on 9 March 1946, a human crush killed 33 spectators. Despite the disaster, the match continued, causing Stoke player [[Stanley Matthews]] to later say that he was sickened that the game was allowed to continue.<ref>{{Citation |last=Matthews |first=Stanley |first2=Les |last2=Scott |title=The Way It Was |publisher=[[Headline Publishing Group|Headline]] |page=222 |year=2000 |isbn=0-7472-6427-9}}</ref>\n\n===The Matthews Final===\nThe final of 1953 is known as the [[Matthews Final]]. The match between [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] and [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] saw [[Stanley Matthews]], at the age of 38, in his third attempt to win an FA Cup winner's medal for Blackpool. Bolton were 3\u20131 up with 22 minutes remaining and, despite being reduced to nine fit men through severe injury to two players, looked set to win the match when Blackpool's [[Stan Mortensen]] scored from a Matthews cross. With less than five minutes remaining Blackpool equalised from a Mortensen free kick (his [[Hat-trick#Association football|hat-trick]], which remains the only one ever scored in a Wembley FA Cup Final) and shortly after the restart, with everybody anticipating extra time, Matthews passed to [[Bill Perry (footballer)|Bill Perry]] who put the ball in the back of the net securing a 4\u20133 victory for Blackpool.\n\n===Bert Trautmann===\nThe final of 1956 saw Manchester City win 3\u20131 against Birmingham City. Roughly 15 minutes before the end of the game, Man City's goalkeeper [[Bert Trautmann]] (a German who had been taken as a [[prisoner of war]] by the British in 1945) injured his neck when he made a save at the feet of Birmingham's [[Peter Murphy (footballer born 1922)|Peter Murphy]]. Despite being in terrible pain he continued to play till the end of match and collected his winners' medal still clutching his neck. An [[X-ray]] later revealed that he had broken a vertebra in his neck.\n\n===Hillsborough disaster===\n{{Main article|Hillsborough disaster}}\nIn 1989 during the opening minutes of the FA Cup semi-final between [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]], 96 people were crushed to death because of overcrowding.<ref name=\"Tragedy to truth\">{{cite news|title=Hillsborough Disaster: From tragedy to truth|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/timelines/zpdc7hv|accessdate=19 April 2018|work=BBC News|date=10 May 2016|language=en}}</ref> Liverpool went on to beat [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] 3\u20132 in the final. The Hillsborough inquest states fans were unlawfully killed due to the lack of police support.<ref name=\"Tragedy to truth\"/>\n\n===Fabrice Muamba===\nOn 17 March 2012, a Fifth Round tie between [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] was abandoned after 41 minutes with the score at 1\u20131, when Bolton midfielder [[Fabrice Muamba]] suffered a [[cardiac arrest]] on the pitch.  Muamba later retired from the sport following medical advice, after his heart stopped beating for 78 minutes and remained in intensive care for two weeks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17460781 |title=Fabrice Muamba was 'dead' for 78 minutes \u2013 Bolton doctor |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 March 2012 |accessdate=24 March 2012}}</ref> Tottenham won the rearranged fixture 3\u20131.\n\n===Minnows, cup runs and giant killings===\nIn 1894, [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] became the first club outside the top division to win the FA Cup: Notts County finished 3rd in [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]] that season. However, as they have not won the FA Cup since then, this means that Notts County have been waiting longer than any other winning professional club to win the trophy for a second time. Their first ever final appearance had come three year's earlier in 1891, where they were defeated 3\u20131 by [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] at [[The Oval]], despite having beaten the same side 7\u20131 in the league only a week earlier.\n\nIn 1901 [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] became the first team from outside the Football League to win the FA Cup since the league was founded, with a 3\u20131 replay victory over [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]].\n\n1958 saw Leeds United beaten 2\u20131 at home to Cardiff City in the third round for the third consecutive year.\n\nIn 1958\u201359, [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] club [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] had one of the great cup runs, beating [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and holding [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] to a draw in the semi-final before losing the replay.  Their progress from the First Round proper included wins over Ilford, Swindon Town (replay), Manchester United, Cardiff City, Tottenham Hotspur, Sheffield United (replay).\n\nWhen [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] beat Leeds United 1\u20130 in the [[FA Cup Final 1973|1973 FA Cup Final]], Sunderland were the first Cup winners from outside the top flight since [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] in 1931. The feat was repeated twice over the next seven seasons (by [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in 1976 and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in 1980) but has not been accomplished since.\n\nIn 1980, [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] became the last side to date to win the competition from outside the top division in football. They were a [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] outfit when they beat holders Arsenal 1\u20130 thanks to a goal by [[Trevor Brooking]]. Four second-level clubs \u2013 [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] in 1982, Sunderland in 1992, [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] in 2004 and Cardiff City in 2008 \u2013 have since reached the final, though all four lost.\n\nIn 1984, [[Johnny Hore]]'s [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] side narrowly missed out on being the first [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] side to reach the final. In a tense semi-final at [[Villa Park]], [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] came out on top, 1\u20130 victors. Starting in the first round proper, Argyle had beaten [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] (in a replay), [[Barking F.C.|Barking]], [[Newport County F.C.|Newport County]] (in a replay), [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]], [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] (in a replay).<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/fa_cup/6426535.stm Where are they now?] BBC Sport, 8 March 2007</ref>\n\nIn 1989, [[Sutton United 2\u20131 Coventry City (1989)|Sutton United beat Coventry City]] 2\u20131 at Gander Green Lane. Sutton United were in the Conference at the time, whilst Coventry were in the First Division, and had won the cup 18 months earlier. This was the last occasion that a non-League club beat a top division club in the FA Cup until Luton Town defeated Norwich City in the 4th round in 2012\u201313 season.\n\nOn 11 December 2007 [[Chasetown F.C.|Chasetown]] became the smallest team ever to reach the FA Cup third round. The [[Southern League Division One Midlands]] side stunned League One Port Vale as Danny Smith's last-minute goal sealed a 1\u20130 win after Port Vale missed two penalties. There was a five division gap between the two teams.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/football_league/article3041096.ece Chasetown hopeful of hosting tie at home] The Times, 12 December 2007</ref>\n\nPremier League side [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] [[Norwich City 0\u20131 Luton Town (2013)|lost at home]] to non-League [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] in the [[2012\u201313 FA Cup]] competition. This was the first time a non-league side had defeated top flight opposition since 1989, and the first time that a non-League side had won away at a top flight side since [[Altrincham F.C.|Altrincham]] had won at [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] in 1985\u201386.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/jan/26/norwich-city-luton-town-fa-cup Luton Town's Scott Rendell makes FA Cup history as Norwich City fall], The Guardian, 26 January 2013</ref>\n\nThe [[2016\u201317 FA Cup]] had two non-League teams reaching the fifth round; [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] and Sutton United, both of the [[National League (division)|National League]]. Sutton United's run included a 3\u20131 win away to [[EFL League One|League One]] side [[AFC Wimbledon]] in a third round replay and a 1\u20130 win at home to [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] of the [[EFL Championship|Championship]] in the fourth round, before succumbing 2\u20130 to eventual winners [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in the fifth round. Lincoln City became the first non-League side in 103 years to reach the quarter-final stage of the FA Cup, since [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.]] of the [[Southern Football League]] in [[1913\u201314 FA Cup|1913\u201314]], and the first outright since the non-League became part of the [[English football league system]] as opposed to running parallel to it. Their run included a 3\u20132 victory over League One [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] in the second round, two Championship scalps in rounds three and four \u2014 a 1\u20130 replay win against [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] and 3\u20131 against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]], respectively \u2014 before [[Burnley F.C. 0\u20131 Lincoln City F.C. (2017)|a 1\u20130 win]] away to [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] of the [[Premier League]] in the fifth round. Lincoln City were eventually knocked out in the quarter-finals, a 5\u20130 reversal at Arsenal.\n\n===Come-backs===\nIn 1966, Everton became only the second side ever to win the cup after being two goals down, without the need of extra time. The Merseysiders had gone two goals down with thirty-one minutes remaining before coming back to win 3\u20132, emulating Blackpool's achievement of thirteen years earlier, however, while Blackpool had been up against a Bolton side reduced to nine fit men, Sheffield Wednesday, by contrast, were in no way handicapped. The match, however, was largely forgotten as it was overshadowed by England's [[1966 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] victory later that year.\n\n==Records and statistics==\n\n===Individual records===\n\n====Most wins and final appearances====\nThe record for most FA Cup wins by a player is held by [[Ashley Cole]], who has won it seven times (with [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in 2002, 2003 and 2005, and [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in 2007, 2009, 2010 and 2012). With Chelsea's victory over Portsmouth in the [[2010 FA Cup Final|2010 final]], Cole beat the record of five jointly held by [[Charles Wollaston]] ([[Wanderers F.C.|Wanderers]]), [[Arthur Kinnaird, 11th Lord Kinnaird|Arthur Kinnaird]] ([[Wanderers F.C.|Wanderers]] & [[Old Etonians F.C.|Old Etonians]]) and [[Jimmy Forrest (footballer)|Jimmy Forrest]] ([[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]).\n\nCole has appeared in 8 finals, having also been on the losing side for Arsenal in 2001.\n\nThe record for most FA Cup wins by a manager is held by [[Ars\u00e8ne Wenger]], who won it seven times (with [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in 1998, 2002, 2003, 2005, 2014, 2015 and 2017.\n\n====Most goals====\nNotts County's [[Harry Cursham]] has scored the most goals in the FA Cup, with 49 goals in 44 appearances from 1877\u201391. Cursham has held the record continuously since 1887. The closest anyone has come to breaking this long-standing record was [[Ian Rush]], who scored 44 FA Cup goals in his career, from 1979\u201398.\n\nW. \"Doc\" Dowden scored 19 FA Cup goals for [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] in the 1929/30 season. This is believed to be the record for one individual in a season. For rounds proper only, the highest total is that of Albert Brown who scored 15 times for Tottenham in 1900/01.\n\nWhen [[Peter Osgood]] scored for Chelsea in the 1970 final, he became the last player to date (and ninth in total) to score in every round of the cup.\n\nIn one tie, between Bournemouth & Boscombe Athletic vs. Margate, [[Ted MacDougall]] scored 9 of Bournemouth's goals in their 11\u20130 victory.\n\n====Scoring firsts====\nIn 1876, [[Thomas Hughes (footballer)|Thomas Hughes]] was the first to score more than once in the final, in a replay match in which Wanderers defeated Old Etonians 3\u20130. In the same final, [[Alexander Bonsor]] from the losing side became the first to score in two consecutive finals (both of which his team lost).\n\n[[Eddie Kelly (footballer)|Eddie Kelly]] from Arsenal became the first substitute to score when he came on the pitch in the 70th minute of the 1971 final and scored in the 96th. [[Stuart McCall]] from Everton scored two goals after coming in from the bench in the 1989 final in the 90th and 102nd minutes.\n\nIn 2001, [[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.]] goalkeeper [[Tony Roberts (footballer)|Tony Roberts]] became the first goalkeeper in the history of the tournament to score a goal, this happened in a Fourth Round Qualifying game against [[Basingstoke Town]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/low/football/fa_cup/2695925.stm BBC News, 27 January 2003]</ref>\n\n====Scoring streaks====\nIn 1886, [[James Brown (footballer born 1862)|Jimmy Brown]] of [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] became the first to score in three consecutive finals from 1884 to 1886 (winning all three).\n\nIn 1887, Aston Villa legend [[Archie Hunter]] became the first player to score in every round of the FA Cup in Villa's victorious 1887 campaign (beginning from the second round, as Villa had a bye in the first). This feat was bettered in 1901 by [[Sandy Brown (Scottish footballer born 1879)|Sandy Brown]] of Tottenham Hotspur, who scored in all rounds from the first.\n\n[[File:Drogba chelsea.jpg|thumb|upright=0.85|In 2012, [[Didier Drogba]] of Chelsea became the first player to score in four FA Cup Finals]]\nIn the 2012 final, [[Didier Drogba]] became the first player to score in four FA Cup Finals.\n\n====Fastest goals====\n[[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa's]] [[Bob Chatt]] scored the winner in the [[1895 FA Cup Final]] with the then-fastest goal after just 30 seconds;<ref name=\"Chatt\">{{cite web|title=FA Cup Trivia |work=www.thefa.com |url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2003/05/48711.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20040106155319/http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2003/05/48711.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=6 January 2004 |accessdate=18 May 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> his record stood until broken by [[Louis Saha]] in [[2009 FA Cup Final|2009]], who scored in 25 seconds.<ref name = \"Saha\">{{cite news | title= Chelsea 2\u20131 Everton  | work= [[BBC Sport]]| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/8060989.stm| accessdate=31 May 2009 | date=30 May 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Louis Saha, Everton.jpg|thumb|upright=0.85|[[Louis Saha]] of Everton scored in a record 25 seconds in the [[2009 FA Cup Final]]]]\nOn 30 May 2009, [[Louis Saha]] scored the fastest ever goal in an FA Cup Final (after 25 seconds) for Everton, who lost 2\u20131 to eventual winners Chelsea.<ref name = \"Saha\"/>\n\nOn 13 February 2010, [[Jimmy Kebe]] of [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] scored the fastest goal in the FA Cup proper after just 9 seconds of Reading's Fifth Round tie against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]].<ref>[http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/FACompetitions/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/2010/quickest-goal-150210.aspx Quick goal in The Cup]</ref>\n\n====Hat\u2013tricks====\n[[William Townley]] scored the first hat\u2013trick in an FA Cup final for [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] when they beat [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C|Sheffield Wednesday]] 6\u20131 in [[1890 FA Cup Final|1890]].\n\nIn [[1894 FA Cup Final|1894]], [[James Logan (footballer, born 1870)|Jimmy Logan]] became the second player to score three goals in the final of the competition, with his [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] beating [[Bolton Wanderers F.C|Bolton Wanderers]] 4\u20131.\n\nThe third hat-trick in an FA Cup final was scored by [[Stan Mortensen]] for [[Blackpool F.C|Blackpool]] against [[Bolton Wanderers]] in the [[1953 FA Cup Final]].\n\nIn 1922, [[England national amateur football team|England amateur]] international Wilfred Minter created an unusual scoring record. In an era when there was some dispute whether or not a hat\u2013trick had to be scored as consecutive goals, Minter performed the feat twice in one match, as well as scoring a seventh, as he scored all of [[St Albans City F.C.|St Albans City]]'s goals against [[Dulwich Hamlet F.C.|Dulwich Hamlet]]. Despite his feat, they actually lost the game 8\u20137.<ref>{{cite book |last= Ward |first= Andrew |title= Soccer's Strangest Matches |year= 1992 |isbn= 0-86051-771-3 |pages=53\u201355}}</ref>\n\n====Penalties====\nThe first penalty in the final was not converted until 1910, with [[Albert Shepherd]] scoring from the spot in the Newcastle 2\u20130 Barnsley replay. The first missed penalty occurred in 1913, with [[Charlie Wallace]] from Aston Villa being the unlucky player, although Villa did win 1\u20130 over Sunderland. Two penalties were not converted until 1994, when [[Eric Cantona]] kicked from the spot in the 60th and 66th minutes to contribute to Manchester United's 4\u20130 win over Chelsea.\n\n[[File:Beasant.jpg|thumb|[[Dave Beasant]] of Wimbledon was the first goalkeeper to save a penalty in an FA Cup Final, in 1988]]\nIn 1988, [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]]'s [[Dave Beasant]] became the first goalkeeper to save a penalty in an [[FA Cup Final 1988|FA Cup final]] at Wembley, when he denied [[John Aldridge]] of [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] (although Charlie Wallace of Aston Villa was the first to miss a penalty in the final). Wimbledon defeated the league champions Liverpool 1\u20130 in that game, and so Beasant also became the first goalkeeper to captain an FA Cup-winning side.<ref>[http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2002/11/30680.htm At the Captain's Table: Dave Beasant] The FA, 15 November 2002</ref>\n\n====Own goals====\nIn 1877, [[Arthur Kinnaird, 11th Lord Kinnaird|Lord Kinnaird]] scored the first own goal in the final with Wanderers defeating Oxford University 2\u20131.\n\nIn [[1946 FA Cup Final|the 1946 final]], [[Bert Turner (footballer born 1909)|Bert Turner]] from Charlton Athletic became famous for scoring for both sides \u2013 first he put a goal in his own net, only to equalise from a free kick a minute later. Tommy Hutchison would repeat the feat (in reverse) for Manchester City in 1981.<ref name=\"Collett 2003 790\">{{cite book |last= Collett |first= Mike |title= The Complete Record of The FA Cup |year= 2003 |isbn= 1-899807-19-5 |pages=790}}</ref>\n\n====Age records====\n[[Billy Hampson]] of [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], the oldest FA Cup finalist, was 41 years and 257 days old when his side beat Aston Villa 2\u20130 in the 1924 Final.\n\nIn 1983 [[Norman Whiteside]], at 18, became the youngest player ever to score in an FA Cup final, whilst playing for Manchester United against [[brighton]]. As of 2017 this record remains unbroken.<ref>[http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/History/Postings/2006/01/FACupHistory_CupHeroes.htm FA Cup Heroes]{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} The FA, 13 January 2006</ref>\n\nIn 2004 [[Curtis Weston]] of [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] became the youngest ever player to play in the final at the age of 17 years and 119 days, beating the record of [[James F. M. Prinsep]] of [[Old Etonians F.C.|Old Etonians]] set in the [[1879 FA Cup Final|1879 Final]].\n\n====Disciplinary firsts====\nIn 1985, [[Kevin Moran (footballer)|Kevin Moran]] of [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] became the first player to be sent off in an FA Cup Final, he had fouled Peter Reid with a sliding tackle which missed the ball.<ref>[http://observer.guardian.co.uk/osm/story/0,,1720888,00.html Kevin Moran] The Observer, 5 March 2006</ref> United went on to win the match 1\u20130, after extra time. Since then, only four other players have been sent off in the FA Cup Final: [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio Reyes]] for [[Arsenal F.C.| Arsenal]] in 2005, [[Pablo Zabaleta]] for [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in 2013, [[Chris Smalling]] of Manchester United in 2016, and [[Victor Moses]] of Chelsea in 2017. Of these, only Moran received a straight red and Zabaleta and Moses ended up being on the losing side.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36292265</ref>\n\n====Accident firsts====\nAt the first Final in 1872, [[Edmund Cresswell]] broke his [[collarbone]] in a charge for Royal Engineers against Wanderers ten minutes into the match, but insisted on continuing play, in goal for the duration of the match, \"although completely disabled and in severe pain\", according to [[The Sportsman (1865 newspaper)|''The Sportsman'']]'s report.<ref>{{cite book|last=Warsop|first=Keith|title=The Early F.A. Cup Finals and the Southern Amateurs, A Who's Who and Match Facts 1872 to 1883|year=2004|publisher=Tony Brown Soccerdata|pages=40,71|isbn=1-899468-78-1}}</ref>\n\n[[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] left back [[Gerry Byrne (footballer, born 1938)|Gerry Byrne]] suffered an identical injury during the [[1965 FA Cup Final|1965 FA Cup final]] against [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]]. Byrne, who had a reputation for being as hard as nails, broke his [[collarbone]] as early as the 3rd minute. Despite being in agony, he played on for the next 87 minutes, and also an additional half hour of extra time. Despite the crippling injury he achieved legendary status, by not only helping [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] to win the cup for the first time in their history, following a 2\u20131 victory, but he also managed to provide an assist, breaking forward on the left and crossing for [[Roger Hunt]] to score the opening goal.\n\nIt has been otherwise commonplace for Cup Final players to continue playing despite injury. The first injured player forced to retire from a match was [[Arthur Dunn]] ([[Old Etonians F.C.|Old Etonians]]), who injured a knee 15 minutes into the second half against [[Blackburn Olympic F.C.|Blackburn Olympic]] in 1883. His team carried on playing with ten men but lost.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Early F.A. Cup Finals|page=53}}</ref>\n\n====Nationality firsts====\nIn 1872, [[Edward Ernest Bowen]] became the first non-Englishman to win the FA Cup. In 1873, [[Julian Sturgis]] was the first man from outside the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]] to win the Cup.\n\nIn 1996, [[Eric Cantona]] became the first non-British or Irish player to captain a winning side in the FA Cup Final.\n\nIn 1997, [[Ruud Gullit]] became the first overseas manager to win the FA Cup, as his Chelsea side beat Middlesbrough 2\u20130. [[Roberto Di Matteo]] scored what was then the fastest goal in a Wembley cup final, after 42 seconds.\n\n====Other individual firsts====\nIn the 1946 final, [[Arthur Turner (footballer born 1922)|Arthur Turner]], of Charlton Athletic, became the only player to play in the final who never played a League game for his club, since the [[the Football League|League's]] inception.<ref name=\"Collett 2003 790\"/>\n\nThe 2003 Final was the first in which a goalkeeper was substituted. [[Paul Jones (footballer, born 1967)|Paul Jones]] replaced the injured [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] goalkeeper [[Antti Niemi (footballer)|Antti Niemi]].\n\nIn the 2012 final, [[John Terry]] became the first player to captain the same team to four FA Cup victories.\n\n===Team records===\n\n====Most goals====\n[[File:Kettering Town v Boston United.jpg|thumb|James Brighton celebrates with Liam Canavan who scores for Kettering Town against Boston United - The club's 868th goal in the competition]]\n\nAs of 3 March 2020, [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]] hold the record for scoring the most number of goals in FA Cup history - netting a total of 891 times between 1888 and 2019, with [[Oliver Burgess|Ollie Burgess]] scoring the 800th goal against [[St Albans City F.C.|St Albans City]] on 11 October 2005 whilst going on to score a hat-trick. \n\n[[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] are second in the list with 883 goals. \n\n[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] are third with 874 goals.\n\nFourth are Manchester United on 868 goals. Fifth are Aston Villa on 846 goals.\n\n====Winning streaks====\nAfter winning the competition from 1884 to 1886, [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] became the second club to win three consecutive FA Cups and remain the only club still in existence to win \"three in a row\" to this day, as Wanderers, who achieved the feat 6 years earlier, were disbanded in 1883.\n\n[[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] hold the record for holding the FA Cup the longest, but only by virtue of the suspension of the competition for World War II.\n\n====Undefeated streaks====\nIn 2013, Chelsea set a record of 29 FA Cup matches without defeat (excluding penalty shoot-outs). Their loss to Manchester City in the 2013 semi-finals was their first since a quarter-final loss to Barnsley in 2008.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21921311 Chelsea 1\u20130 Man Utd]</ref>\n\nArsenal are currently the holders of the most FA Cup trophies (13).\n\n====Most final losses====\nIn 1969 Leicester City lost their fourth FA Cup Final, 1\u20130 to Manchester City. No other team has made it to the Final so many times without ever winning. However, 13 other teams have lost as many or more Finals but have also won the Cup at least once. The record number of Final defeats stands at 8 for Everton, although they have also won the Cup on 5 occasions.\n\n===Game records===\nOn 15 October 1887, [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] defeated [[Hyde F.C.|Hyde]] 26\u20130, which remains the record score in an FA Cup tie.\n\nIn 1903 [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] defeated [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] 6\u20130, a record that was matched by [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in 2019, when they defeated Watford 6\u20130. \n\nIn 1959, [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] became the first team to lose a player to injury in the Final and go on to win with 10 men, beating Luton Town 2\u20131 after having goalscorer [[Roy Dwight]] carried off with a broken leg after 33 minutes.\n\n1971 saw the longest tie in Cup history. [[Oxford City F.C.|Oxford City]] and [[Alvechurch F.C.|Alvechurch]] play 6 games for a total of 660 minutes. Alvechurch won the final game 1\u20130 to progress to the first round proper.\n\n====Tournament game streaks====\nIn 1963, [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] became the quickest winners of all time, apart from the special circumstances of [[1873 FA Cup Final|1873]]. They played their first match on 4 March, after 12 postponements, and won the final on 25 May, 82 days later.<ref>{{cite book |last= Collett |first= Mike |title= The Complete Record of The FA Cup |year= 2003 |isbn= 1-899807-19-5 |pages=782}}</ref>\n\nThe 1973\u201374 competition saw the record set for the highest number of games played in one season by one club. [[Bideford F.C.|Bideford]] played 13 games over five rounds: one for the 1st qualifying round, two for the 2nd qualifying round, five for the 3rd qualifying round, four for the 4th qualifying round, and one for the 1st round proper. Multiple replays no longer take place, so this record is unlikely to be beaten.\n\n===Competition records===\n1910 saw the start of a string of 14 consecutive finals (including 3 replays, thus 17 matches) in which the losing side failed to score. This series was not approached until 1994\u20132000, with seven consecutive finals (no replays).\n\nIn 1948, [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] became the only team to win the FA Cup after being drawn against top-division opposition in every round.\n\n1956\u201357 saw the record for highest number of rounds played in a row, when former League club [[New Brighton A.F.C.|New Brighton]] played in nine rounds. They started in the preliminary round, and progressed through four qualifying rounds to the fourth round proper, where they lost to [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]. They had just one replay \u2013 for their first round tie. The 1977\u201378 competition saw this record equalled by [[Blyth Spartans F.C.|Blyth Spartans]], who progressed from the 1st qualifying round to the 5th round proper. The games for the 2nd qualifying round and the 5th rounds proper went to a replay. The 1979\u201380 competition saw the record equalled again, this time by [[Harlow Town F.C.|Harlow Town]], who progressed from the Preliminary round through four qualifying rounds to the fourth round proper, where they lost to [[Watford F.C.|Watford]]. The matches for the 2nd and 3rd rounds went to a replay.\n\nIn 1959, [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] fielded the same 11 players in every round of the competition (9 matches including replays).\n\n1976\u201377 was the season with the largest number of matches (173) in the competition proper. Due to the abolition of multiple replays, the record is unlikely to be beaten. In seasons after 1996 (when penalty shootouts were introduced) the most ties (163) occurred in 2008\u201309.\n\nA record 763 clubs were accepted for the [[2011\u201312 FA Cup]].\n\n===Penalty shootouts===\nIn the 1971\u201372 competition, [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] became the first team to win a match in a [[penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]], beating [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] 4\u20133 after a 0\u20130 draw in the third-fourth playoff.<ref name=\"complete1\"/>\n\nThe [[2005 FA Cup Final]] between [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] was the first final ever to have to go to [[penalty shootout (football)|penalties]] as the score was still 0\u20130 after extra time. [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] won the shootout \u2013 and thus the Cup \u2013 5\u20134. It was the first 0\u20130 draw in an FA Cup final since 1912.\n\nOn 22 January 2008, [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] became the first club in the FA Cup to miss all four of their penalties in a penalty shootout, against [[Barnet FC|Barnet]] in a third round replay.<ref>\"[http://www.swindonadvertiser.co.uk/mostpopular.var.1989368.mostviewed.is_towns_spot_of_bother_a_record.php Is Town's spot of bother a record?]\" ''Swindon Advertiser''. URL last accessed 24 January 2008</ref>\n\n===Doubles/Trebles===\nIn 1889, Preston North End became the first club to achieve [[Double (association football)|the double]] of winning the FA Cup (beating [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] 3\u20130) and the Football League in the same season. This double was even more extraordinary in that the league was won without a single defeat, a feat which would not be repeated in the top division until 2003\u201304, by [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. Equally impressive was that the cup was won without conceding a single goal. Such was the team's dominance that it was nicknamed [[The Invincibles (football)|\"The Invincibles\"]].\n\nIn 1897 Aston Villa won the FA Cup and League Championship on same day, with results in League matches confirming their championship as they beat Everton 3\u20132 in the final.\n\n1961 saw [[Tottenham Hotspur]] become the first club in the 20th century to win the FA Cup and league championship in the same season, known famously as [[Double (association football)|The Double]]. They also retained the FA Cup the following year.\n\nIn 1986, [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] beat [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] 3\u20131 in the first all-[[Merseyside]] FA Cup final to complete the double and claim their first FA Cup triumph for 12 years. The teams would meet again in the final just 3 years later.\n\nIn 1994, [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] completed the double thanks to a 4\u20130 win over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] at Wembley. [[Eric Cantona]] scored two penalties and the other goals came from [[Mark Hughes]] and [[Brian McClair]].\n\nIn 1996, a late goal from [[Eric Cantona]] saw [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] become the first team to win the double twice as they beat [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] 1\u20130 at Wembley, a week after clinching the league title and overtake Tottenham's total of eight cup wins.\n\nIn 1998, [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] beat Newcastle 2\u20130. This was the second time Arsenal had done the domestic double, which includes winning the Premier League and FA Cup in the same year.\n\nIn 1999, Manchester United completed [[The Treble]] by also winning the [[Premier League|FA Premier League]] and the [[UEFA Champions League]].\n\nIn 2002, [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] matched [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]'s record of three doubles as they defeated [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] 2\u20130 at the [[Millennium Stadium]] and clinched the league title four days later.\n\nIn May 2010, Chelsea became the seventh club to complete the league and FA Cup \"[[Double (association football)#England|Double]]\", by beating [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] 1\u20130 in the 2010 final.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/8680493.stm Chelsea 1\u20130 Portsmouth]</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Manchester City became the first English side to win the [[Treble (association football)#Domestic trebles|domestic treble]] with their Cup win, having already secured the [[EFL Cup]] and the Premier League.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McNulty |first1=Phil |title=Man City 6-0 Watford: City clinch historic domestic treble |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48236232 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] also won the [[Welsh Cup]] in the year of their FA Cup win in 1927, becoming the only team in the world to achieve a transnational cup double.\n\n==Oddities==\nIn 1873, [[Sheffield F.C.|Sheffield]] confirmed a unique place in FA Cup history, knocking out [[Shropshire Wanderers F.C.|Shropshire Wanderers]] on the toss of a coin; the only time a tie has been decided in this way.<ref>{{cite book |last= Collett |first= Mike |title= The Complete Record of The FA Cup |year= 2003 |isbn= 1-899807-19-5 |page=537}}</ref>\n\nThe only game to be played on [[Christmas Day]] took place in 1888, [[Linfield F.C.|Linfield Athletic]] beating [[Cliftonville F.C.|Cliftonville]] 7\u20130.<ref name=\"Collett 2003 878\"/>\n\nIn 1921, [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham]] set the record for shortest FA Cup run \u2013 they forgot to send in their entry form.\n\nIn 1931 West Bromwich Albion became the only team to win the FA Cup and get promoted in the same season, defeating Birmingham City 2\u20131 in the final.\n\nIn 1990, [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] won the competition in a replay against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]. This was United manager [[Alex Ferguson]]'s first trophy at United, and this success is seen by many as having saved him from being dismissed after 4 unsuccessful seasons.\n\nFor the first time, the FA Cup was played under a roof in the final of the [[2002\u201303 in English football|2002\u201303 season]], held on 17 May 2003 at the [[Millennium Stadium]] in [[Cardiff]], with [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] benefiting from cover from the rain. Arsenal were 1\u20130 winners.\n\n[[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] became the first side to win the FA Cup and be relegated in the same season, after beating [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] 1\u20130 in the [[2013 FA Cup Final|2013 final]]. Their fate in the Premier League was sealed three days after their triumph, following a 4\u20131 defeat to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22430454 | work=BBC News | title=Arsenal 4\u20131 Wigan | date=14 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Participants==\n\n===Amateur, university and professional teams===\nIn 1883 [[Blackburn Olympic F.C.|Blackburn Olympic]] broke the \"old order of things\" to defeat [[Old Etonians F.C.|Old Etonians]] in the final to become the first professional club to win the trophy. The win marked a turning point in the culture of the game in England.\n\nIn 2002, [[Team Bath F.C.|Team Bath]] (from the [[University of Bath]]) became the first university team to enter the competition since [[Gonville & Caius A.F.C.|Gonville & Caius]] in 1881, and progressed through the qualifying rounds before being knocked out in the first round proper by [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]].\n\n===Scottish sides===\nIn 1884 and 1885 Scottish side [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]] reached the final, the first time a non-English side had done so. They lost both times. (Scotland had had its own [[Scottish Cup]] since 1873.) (See also: [[Scottish clubs in the FA Cup]])\n\n===Welsh sides===\nIn 1914 [[Swansea City F.C.|Swansea Town]] became the first club from South Wales to reach the second round. They were beaten 2\u20131 by QPR.\n\nThe 1927 final resulted in a [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] victory over [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. To the present day, Cardiff City are the only non-English-based team to win the trophy.\n\n==Traditions==\n\n===Ribbons===\nIn 1901, Tottenham became the first team to attach ribbons in their team colours to the trophy, a tradition that continues to this day.\n\n===Equipment===\nIn the 1933 final, Everton players wore shirts numbered 1\u201311, and Manchester City players 12\u201322. This was the first major competitive game ever to have the players' shirts numbered.\n\nThe [[FA Cup Final 1973|1973 FA Cup Final]] was the first that a yellow ball was used in a Cup Final (although an orange ball had been used in previous finals, for example in 1968).  An orange ball was used in the [[2014 FA Cup Final|2014]] and [[2015 FA Cup Final|2015 Cup Final]]s, as they were used throughout the competition.\n\n===Referees===\nSince 1902, referees can only officiate one Cup Final, though they are allowed to have prior Final experience as an assistant referee.\n\n===Royal attendance===\nIn 1914, [[George V of the United Kingdom|George V]] became the first monarch to watch the FA Cup Final between [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the last cup final played at [[Crystal Palace National Sports Centre|Crystal Palace]].\n\nThe 'Matthews Final' of 1953 was the first football match attended by [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|The Queen]], in her Coronation year.<ref>[http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/page4829.asp 80 facts about the Queen] British Monarchy</ref>\n\n===Triangular corner flags===\nIt is commonly held that previous winners of the FA Cup are traditionally the only clubs allowed to use [[triangular corner flags in English football]]. However, this tradition is not affirmed in the FA's lawbook.\n\n==Greatest goals==\nThe 1981 final contained what many consider to be the greatest ever final goal,<ref>[http://football.guardian.co.uk/pictures/image/0,8556,-10604601121,00.html Best ever FA cup final goal] The Guardian, 7 February 2003</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/sports_talk/1765630.stm Your favourite FA Cup goal] BBC Sport, 17 January 2002</ref> scored by Tottenham's [[Ricky Villa]] who beat several players in a mazy run before slotting the ball home.\n\nIn 1999, [[Ryan Giggs]] of Manchester United scored in [[extra time]] to defeat Arsenal 2\u20131 in FA Cup semi-final replay. The goal was voted the greatest in FA Cup history in 2003.<ref>[http://www.icons.org.uk/theicons/collection/fa-cup/features/greatest-fa-cup-goals The Greatest FA Cup Goals] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090822000000/http://www.icons.org.uk/theicons/collection/fa-cup/features/greatest-fa-cup-goals |date=22 August 2009 }} Icons</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n===Bibliography===\n{{cite book |title=We Won the Cup: A Celebration for the 100th F.A.Cup Final|date= 10 April 1981|first= David |last=Barber |publisher=Pan Books|isbn= 978-0330264013 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{FA Cup Seasons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of The Fa Cup}}\n[[Category:FA Cup]]\n[[Category:History of football in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\nThe '''history of the [[FA Cup]]''' in association football dates back to [[1871\u201372 FA Cup|1871\u201372]]. Aside from suspensions during the [[First World War|First]] and [[Second World War]]s, the competition has been played every year since.\n\n==History==\n\n===19th century===\n[[File:1stRoyalEngineers.png|thumb|right|The [[Royal Engineers A.F.C.|Royal Engineers]] squad that played the first [[FA Cup]] final in [[1872 FA Cup Final|1872]]]]\nOn 20 July 1871, in the offices of [[The Sportsman (1865 newspaper)|''The Sportsman'' newspaper]], [[C. W. Alcock]] proposed to [[The Football Association]] committee that \"it is desirable that a Challenge Cup should be established in connection with the Association for which all clubs belonging to the Association should be invited to compete\". The other committee members were:<ref>{{cite book |title= The Complete Record of the FA Cup|last= Collett|first= Mike |year= 2003|publisher= Sports Books|isbn=1-899807-19-5|pages=16\u201317}}</ref>\n* [[Alfred Stair|A. Stair]] (F.A. Treasurer) ([[Upton Park F.C.|Upton Park]])\n* [[Charles W. Stephenson|C.W. Stephenson]] ([[Westminster School]])\n* J.H. Gifford ([[Civil Service F.C.|Civil Service]])\n* D. Allport ([[Crystal Palace F.C. (1861)|Crystal Palace]])\n* [[Morton Betts|M.P. Betts]] ([[Harrow School]])\n* Capt. [[Francis Marindin]] ([[Royal Engineers F.C.|Royal Engineers]])\n\nThe proposition was carried.\n\nThe [[1871\u201372 FA Cup|inaugural FA Cup tournament]] kicked off in November 1871. After thirteen games in all, [[Wanderers F.C.|Wanderers]] were crowned the winners in the final at [[Kennington Oval]], on 16 March 1872.{{sfn|Barber|1981|p=1871\u20132}} The following year, Wanderers retained the title after receiving a bye to the final, the 'Challenge Round', where they beat [[Oxford University A.F.C.|Oxford University]] to retain the Cup. The rules were changed for the following season, to help inspire teams to try to get to the final, instead of knowing who their opponents would be before they reached it.{{fact|date=December 2016}}\n\n1875 saw the first final to be replayed, between Royal Engineers and [[Old Etonians F.C.|Old Etonians]], on Saturday 13 March (score 1-1 after extra time, in the first drawn final) and on Tuesday 16 March (score 2-0 between the respective teams), both times at [[Kennington Oval]].\n\nThe modern cup was beginning to be established by the 1888\u201389 season, when qualifying rounds were introduced, with clubs competing on regional basis until only one was left for the Fourth Qualifying Round, and in the same season, the 'magic of the cup' began when Warwick County became the first non-league side to beat a First Division club on 6 October 1888, winning 2\u20131 away at [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]].<ref name=\"Collett 2003 878\">{{cite book |last= Collett |first= Mike |title= The Complete Record of The FA Cup |year= 2003 |isbn= 1-899807-19-5 |pages=878}}</ref>\n\n===20th century===\n[[File:Facupfinal1901-A.jpg|thumb|1901 FA Cup final at Crystal Palace, Sandy Brown just scored a goal]] \nThe [[1901 FA Cup Final]] was won by London club [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], which became the only [[non-League football|non-League]] club to have ever won the FA Cup final after the formation of the [[Football League]] in 1888 (Tottenham were then in the [[Southern Football League|Southern League]]). The final between Tottenham and [[Sheffield United]] held at [[Crystal_Palace_National_Sports_Centre#Crystal_Palace_FA_Cup_ Finals_1895.E2.80.931914|Crystal Palace]] was attended by 110,820 fans, then the largest crowd ever for a football match.<ref name=\"turf 2\">{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=l67VDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT29&lpg=PT29#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Turf Wars: A History of London Football |first= Steve|last= Tongue |chapter=Chapter 2: Taking Shape (1901-1920)|publisher= Pitch Publishing|isbn=9781785312489  }}</ref>  The game ended in a 2\u20132 draw, with both Spurs goals from [[Sandy Brown (footballer born 1879)|Sandy Brown]], and a disputed goal from Sheffield \u2013 the final was the first to be filmed and it would be the first referee decision demonstrated to be wrong by film footage as it showed that the ball did not cross the line.<ref name=\"turf 2\"/><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S07SDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT11&lpg=PT11#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=People's History of Tottenham Hotspur: How Spurs Fans Shaped the Identity of One of the World\u2019s Most Famous Clubs|authors= Martin Cloake, Alan Fisher |publisher= Pitch Publishing |date=15 August 2016 |chapter=Introduction}}</ref> The replay was held at [[Burnden Park]], Bolton on 27 April 1901, which Spurs won 3\u20131. \n\nIn the [[1915 FA Cup Final|1915 final]], [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] beat [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] 3\u20130 at [[Old Trafford (football ground)|Old Trafford]]. The final became known as \"The Khaki Cup Final\" owing to the large number of uniformed soldiers in attendance. This year the FA Cup competition was controversial as the [[First World War]] had started, and concerns were raised about the appropriateness of football competition continuing in the midst of a world war. The Football Association however argued that it would be better to carry on to provide relief for the workers and soldiers.{{sfn|Barber|1981|p=1914\u20135}} In the following year the competition was suspended.\n\nThe [[1923 FA Cup Final|1923 final]] was the first FA Cup final to be played at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]], which was known at the time as the Empire Stadium. Over 200,000 people squeezed into a stadium meant for 127,000 and many spilt out onto the pitch. It took three-quarter of an hour for mounted police to clear the field before the game could start. [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] beat [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]] 2\u20130 in the match.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s9ak2PkMzDwC&pg=PA89#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Now You Know Soccer|first= Doug |last=Lennox |publisher= Dundurn |date=1 June 2009 |isbn= 9781770706132}}</ref> \n\nThe practice of teams from the top two divisions receiving exemption to the Third Round of the competition began in the 1925/26 season.{{fact|date=December 2016}} The [[1926 FA Cup Final|1926 final]] is the first to be played under a change to the offside rule.{{sfn|Barber|1981|p=1925\u20136}}\n\nThe [[1945\u201346 in English football|1945\u20131946]] FA Cup was the first played since the competition was suspended during [[World War II]]. For one season only, as the intermediate [[Football League North and South|Football League North and Football League South]] were of variable quality, to boost clubs' income each tie was played over two legs (one home, one away with the scores being added together to decide who went through) to increase the number of matches in the season. Matches that were level at the end of both legs were replayed at the stadium of whichever team had played the second leg away. The final, played at a neutral venue, remained a single match affair, decided by extra time if teams were level after 90 minutes. The final was won by [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] 4\u20131.{{sfn|Barber|1981|p=1945\u20136}}\n\nIn the [[1966\u201367 FA Cup]] the first substitutes were allowed after many years of finals proving unbalanced due to injuries which forced players into leaving the field early. Players had suffered broken bones in the 1957, 1959, 1960, 1961 and 1965 finals. They were not, however, used in the final until the next year in the [[1968 FA Cup Final]], when [[Dennis Clarke]] replaced [[John Kaye (footballer)|John Kaye]] for West Bromwich Albion.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/when-saturday-comes-blog/2015/sep/18/fifty-years-substitutions-football-sport |title=Fifty years of substitutions in football: from necessary novelties to tactical tools |first=Peter |last=Bateman |work=The Guardian |date=18 September 2015 }}</ref>\n\n1970 saw the first Wembley final to go to a replay. The replayed final was played at [[Old Trafford (football ground)|Old Trafford]] due to the damaged state of the Wembley pitch caused by the Horse of the Year Show and was contested between [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]]. 1970 also saw the first [[FA Cup Third-fourth place matches|third place play-off]] with Manchester United beating Watford 2\u20130. This play-off proved short-lived, and the 1973\u201374 competition saw the last 3rd place play-off match, contested by [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] and [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]], with Burnley winning 1\u20130 at [[Filbert Street]].<ref name=\"complete1\">{{cite book |last= Collett |first= Mike |title= The Complete Record of The FA Cup |year= 2003 |isbn= 1-899807-19-5 |pages=795}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1972 FA Cup Final|1972]] the FA Cup celebrated its centenary (though this was not its 100th season, due to interruptions for the two world wars). [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] won the final against holders [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. The [[1973 FA Cup Final]] was the 50th anniversary of Wembley as a venue for the cup final.{{fact|date=December 2016}}\n\n[[File:Ardiles villa fa cup.jpg|thumb|left|170px|[[Osvaldo Ardiles]] and [[Ricardo Villa]] holding the FA Cup trophy won in [[1981 FA Cup Final|1981]]]]\nIn 1981, The [[1981 FA Cup Final|100th FA Cup final]] took place between Tottenham Hotspur and [[Manchester City]].  It finished 1\u20131 after extra time.  For the first time, the replay was held again at Wembley \u2013 previously replayed finals had been held at other neutral grounds. Tottenham won 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29476689 |title=Top 50 FA Cup goals: 'And still Ricky Villa |work=BBC Sport |date=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1990\u201391 FA Cup]], the [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] v [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] fourth round tie had to be replayed three times. After the third replay, The FA decided that from the first round onwards, one replay, then extra time, then a penalty shootout would be a suitable alternative to a fixtures backlog.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/cup-marathon-which-saw-the-fa-blow-whistle-on-multiple-replays-1-7707317 |title=Cup marathon which saw the FA blow whistle on multiple replays|work=Yorkshire Post |date=1 February 2016}}</ref> The semi-final of this year was the first to be played at Wembley, with Tottenham beating Arsenal 3\u20131, including a 30-yard free kick from [[Paul Gascoigne]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/1216438.stm|title=FA Cup revisited: Spurs v Arsenal |work=BBC Sport |date= 5 April 2001}}</ref>\n\nAfter the change in replay rule starting with the season [[1991\u201392 FA Cup]] where multiple replays were replaced by one replay and penalty kicks after extra time, the first penalty takers in the competition proper were [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] and [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]], with Rotherham winning 7\u20136 in a first round replay. In the qualifying rounds, multiple replays lasted until 1996/97, with the game between Morecambe and Lancaster City on 4 November 1996 being the last second replay.<ref>[http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/FACompetitions/TheFACup/Archive.aspx 1996\u20131997 competition results, FA.com]</ref>\n\nIn 1993, both semi-finals were played at Wembley Stadium for the first time ever, one between Arsenal and Tottenham, the other between Sheffield Wednesday and Sheffield United. In 1993, the last ever FA Cup final replay took place, with [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] beating [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] 2\u20131. Arsenal became the first team to win both the FA Cup and the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] in the same season, beating Sheffield Wednesday in both finals, the first time the same teams contested the two cup finals in the same season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/chris-waddle-no-one-remembers-1993-league-cup-final-it-was-rubbish |title=Chris Waddle: No one remembers the 1993 League Cup Final \u2013 it was Rubbish |author=Chris Flanagan|date=26 October 2015 |work=FourFourTwo}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, the last ever FA Cup semi-final replay took place. From 2000 onwards, it was decided that any semi-finals and finals would go first to extra time then penalties, rather than be replayed.{{fact|date=December 2016}} In 1999, under pressure from [[The Football Association|The FA]], Manchester United became the first FA Cup holders not to defend their title when they withdrew from the FA Cup, instead electing to take part in the inaugural [[FIFA Club World Championship]] played in Brazil. To decide who took their place, a \"lucky losers\" draw was held containing the 20 teams knocked out in the second round; [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] were selected.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/sport/football/fa_cup/544737.stm |title=Lucky Darlington land Villa trip |date=1 December 1999 |work=BBC}}</ref>\n\n===21st century===\n[[File:Cfc fa cup2007.jpg|thumb|First [[2007 FA Cup Final|FA Cup Final]] at the new Wembley Stadium in 2007]]\nRedevelopment of Wembley saw the final played outside of England for the first time ever, with the 2001\u20132006 finals being played at the [[Millennium Stadium]] in [[Cardiff]].{{fact|date=December 2016}}\n\nUpon the opening of the new [[Wembley Stadium]], the Final returned to Wembley, but the semi-finals were played at neutral grounds. However, in 2003, it was announced that all future semi-finals would be played at the new Wembley Stadium once it had opened, and this took effect in 2008.{{fact|date=December 2016}}\n\nBeginning with the [[2016\u201317 FA Cup|2016\u201317 competition]], all quarter-final matches will be played to a result on the day (with draws followed by extra time, with a penalty shootout if level after extra time) instead of being replayed in the event of a draw.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.thefa.com/news/the-fa-cup/2016/may/quarter-final-sudden-death-replays |title=No replays in the 2017 Emirates FA Cup quarter-finals |publisher=The Football Association |date=26 May 2016 |accessdate=25 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Broadcasting===\nThe 1927 final was the first ever Cup Final to be broadcast by the [[BBC Radio|BBC]], who produced a numbered grid of the pitch for Radio Times readers to follow the ball. This gave rise to the popular myth of the origin of the phrase, \"[[wikt:back to square one|Back to square one]]\" (i.e. a back-pass to the goalkeeper).{{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}\n\nIn 1938, after 29 minutes of extra time, it was still 0\u20130 between [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston]] and [[Huddersfield Town F.C.|Huddersfield]]. [[BBC Radio]] commentator [[Thomas Woodrooffe]] declared: \"If there's a goal scored now, I'll eat my hat.\" Seconds later Preston was awarded a penalty from which [[George Mutch]] scored. Woodrooffe kept his promise. This was also the first FA Cup Final to be broadcast live by BBC Television.{{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}\n\n==Notable events==\n\n===Inaugural tournament===\nThe [[1871\u201372 FA Cup|inaugural FA Cup tournament]] kicked off in November 1871. Four first-round matches were the first FA Cup games ever played \u2013 on 11 November 1871. The first Cup goal was scored by [[Clapham Rovers F.C.|Clapham Rovers]] player [[Jarvis Kenrick]] in a 3\u20130 win over Upton Park (Kenrick scoring twice in the process). The following year, on 16 March 1872, [[Wanderers F.C.|Wanderers]] became the first winners of the FA Cup, beating [[Royal Engineers A.F.C.|Royal Engineers]] 1\u20130 at [[The Oval]]. Fifteen clubs had entered, only twelve actually played, and there were thirteen games in total. The winning goal was scored by [[Morton Peto Betts]], who played under the pseudonym of 'A.H. Chequer'.\n\n===White Horse Final===\n[[File:White Horse Final1923.jpg|right|thumb|The first FA Cup Final at Wembley in 1923, the crowd at the Cup Final was so large that fans swarmed onto the pitch]]\n\nThe first Wembley FA Cup Final, played on 28 April 1923, was marked by disorderly scenes unparalleled in the history of football. Before the match a massive crowd outside the stadium rushed the gates, burst the barriers and swarmed on to the pitch. Kick-off was delayed for 45 minutes as mounted police, with PC [[George Scorey]] on his white charger \"Billy\" \u2013 hence the [[FA Cup Final 1923|\"White Horse Final\"]] \u2013 particularly visible, encouraged people to move behind the touchlines. [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton]] beat West Ham 2\u20130 and the first Wembley goal was scored after just two minutes by David Jack. It was estimated that 200,000 fans had squeezed into Wembley and Cup Finals were made \"all ticket\" after that.\n\n===Burnden Park disaster===\nDuring a Sixth Round second-leg tie between Bolton and Stoke City on 9 March 1946, a human crush killed 33 spectators. Despite the disaster, the match continued, causing Stoke player [[Stanley Matthews]] to later say that he was sickened that the game was allowed to continue.<ref>{{Citation |last=Matthews |first=Stanley |first2=Les |last2=Scott |title=The Way It Was |publisher=[[Headline Publishing Group|Headline]] |page=222 |year=2000 |isbn=0-7472-6427-9}}</ref>\n\n===The Matthews Final===\nThe final of 1953 is known as the [[Matthews Final]]. The match between [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] and [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] saw [[Stanley Matthews]], at the age of 38, in his third attempt to win an FA Cup winner's medal for Blackpool. Bolton were 3\u20131 up with 22 minutes remaining and, despite being reduced to nine fit men through severe injury to two players, looked set to win the match when Blackpool's [[Stan Mortensen]] scored from a Matthews cross. With less than five minutes remaining Blackpool equalised from a Mortensen free kick (his [[Hat-trick#Association football|hat-trick]], which remains the only one ever scored in a Wembley FA Cup Final) and shortly after the restart, with everybody anticipating extra time, Matthews passed to [[Bill Perry (footballer)|Bill Perry]] who put the ball in the back of the net securing a 4\u20133 victory for Blackpool.\n\n===Bert Trautmann===\nThe final of 1956 saw Manchester City win 3\u20131 against Birmingham City. Roughly 15 minutes before the end of the game, Man City's goalkeeper [[Bert Trautmann]] (a German who had been taken as a [[prisoner of war]] by the British in 1945) injured his neck when he made a save at the feet of Birmingham's [[Peter Murphy (footballer born 1922)|Peter Murphy]]. Despite being in terrible pain he continued to play till the end of match and collected his winners' medal still clutching his neck. An [[X-ray]] later revealed that he had broken a vertebra in his neck.\n\n===Hillsborough disaster===\n{{Main article|Hillsborough disaster}}\nIn 1989 during the opening minutes of the FA Cup semi-final between [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]], 96 people were crushed to death because of overcrowding.<ref name=\"Tragedy to truth\">{{cite news|title=Hillsborough Disaster: From tragedy to truth|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/timelines/zpdc7hv|accessdate=19 April 2018|work=BBC News|date=10 May 2016|language=en}}</ref> Liverpool went on to beat [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] 3\u20132 in the final. The Hillsborough inquest states fans were unlawfully killed due to the lack of police support.<ref name=\"Tragedy to truth\"/>\n\n===Fabrice Muamba===\nOn 17 March 2012, a Fifth Round tie between [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] was abandoned after 41 minutes with the score at 1\u20131, when Bolton midfielder [[Fabrice Muamba]] suffered a [[cardiac arrest]] on the pitch.  Muamba later retired from the sport following medical advice, after his heart stopped beating for 78 minutes and remained in intensive care for two weeks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17460781 |title=Fabrice Muamba was 'dead' for 78 minutes \u2013 Bolton doctor |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 March 2012 |accessdate=24 March 2012}}</ref> Tottenham won the rearranged fixture 3\u20131.\n\n===Minnows, cup runs and giant killings===\nIn 1894, [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] became the first club outside the top division to win the FA Cup: Notts County finished 3rd in [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]] that season. However, as they have not won the FA Cup since then, this means that Notts County have been waiting longer than any other winning professional club to win the trophy for a second time. Their first ever final appearance had come three year's earlier in 1891, where they were defeated 3\u20131 by [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] at [[The Oval]], despite having beaten the same side 7\u20131 in the league only a week earlier.\n\nIn 1901 [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] became the first team from outside the Football League to win the FA Cup since the league was founded, with a 3\u20131 replay victory over [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]].\n\n1958 saw Leeds United beaten 2\u20131 at home to Cardiff City in the third round for the third consecutive year.\n\nIn 1958\u201359, [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] club [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] had one of the great cup runs, beating [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and holding [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] to a draw in the semi-final before losing the replay.  Their progress from the First Round proper included wins over Ilford, Swindon Town (replay), Manchester United, Cardiff City, Tottenham Hotspur, Sheffield United (replay).\n\nWhen [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] beat Leeds United 1\u20130 in the [[FA Cup Final 1973|1973 FA Cup Final]], Sunderland were the first Cup winners from outside the top flight since [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] in 1931. The feat was repeated twice over the next seven seasons (by [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in 1976 and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in 1980) but has not been accomplished since.\n\nIn 1980, [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] became the last side to date to win the competition from outside the top division in football. They were a [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] outfit when they beat holders Arsenal 1\u20130 thanks to a goal by [[Trevor Brooking]]. Four second level clubs \u2013 [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] in 1982, Sunderland in 1992, [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] in 2004 and Cardiff City in 2008 \u2013 have since reached the final, though all four lost.\n\nIn 1984, [[Johnny Hore]]'s [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] side narrowly missed out on being the first [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] side to reach the final. In a tense semi-final at [[Villa Park]], [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] came out on top, 1\u20130 victors. Starting in the first round proper, Argyle had beaten [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] (in a replay), [[Barking F.C.|Barking]], [[Newport County F.C.|Newport County]] (in a replay), [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]], [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] (in a replay).<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/fa_cup/6426535.stm Where are they now?] BBC Sport, 8 March 2007</ref>\n\nIn 1989, [[Sutton United 2\u20131 Coventry City (1989)|Sutton United beat Coventry City]] 2\u20131 at Gander Green Lane. Sutton United were in the Conference at the time, whilst Coventry were in the First Division, and had won the cup 18 months earlier. This was the last occasion that a non-League club beat a top division club in the FA Cup until Luton Town defeated Norwich City in the 4th round in 2012\u201313 season.\n\nOn 11 December 2007 [[Chasetown F.C.|Chasetown]] became the smallest team ever to reach the FA Cup third round. The [[Southern League Division One Midlands]] side stunned League One Port Vale as Danny Smith's last-minute goal sealed a 1\u20130 win after Port Vale missed two penalties. There was a five division gap between the two teams.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/football_league/article3041096.ece Chasetown hopeful of hosting tie at home] The Times, 12 December 2007</ref>\n\nPremier League side [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] [[Norwich City 0\u20131 Luton Town (2013)|lost at home]] to non-League [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] in the [[2012\u201313 FA Cup]] competition. This was the first time a non-league side had defeated top flight opposition since 1989, and the first time that a non-League side had won away at a top flight side since [[Altrincham F.C.|Altrincham]] had won at [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] in 1985\u201386.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/jan/26/norwich-city-luton-town-fa-cup Luton Town's Scott Rendell makes FA Cup history as Norwich City fall], The Guardian, 26 January 2013</ref>\n\nThe [[2016\u201317 FA Cup]] had two non-League teams reaching the fifth round; [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] and Sutton United, both of the [[National League (division)|National League]]. Sutton United's run included a 3\u20131 win away to [[EFL League One|League One]] side [[AFC Wimbledon]] in a third round replay and a 1\u20130 win at home to [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] of the [[EFL Championship|Championship]] in the fourth round, before succumbing 2\u20130 to eventual winners [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in the fifth round. Lincoln City became the first non-League side in 103 years to reach the quarter-final stage of the FA Cup, since [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.]] of the [[Southern Football League]] in [[1913\u201314 FA Cup|1913\u201314]], and the first outright since the non-League became part of the [[English football league system]] as opposed to running parallel to it. Their run included a 3\u20132 victory over League One [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] in the second round, two Championship scalps in rounds three and four \u2014 a 1\u20130 replay win against [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] and 3\u20131 against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]], respectively \u2014 before [[Burnley F.C. 0\u20131 Lincoln City F.C. (2017)|a 1\u20130 win]] away to [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] of the [[Premier League]] in the fifth round. Lincoln City were eventually knocked out in the quarter-finals, a 5\u20130 reversal at Arsenal.\n\n===Come-backs===\nIn 1966, Everton became only the second side ever to win the cup after being two goals down, without the need of extra time. The Merseysiders had gone two goals down with thirty-one minutes remaining before coming back to win 3\u20132, emulating Blackpool's achievement of thirteen years earlier, however, while Blackpool had been up against a Bolton side reduced to nine fit men, Sheffield Wednesday, by contrast, were in no way handicapped. The match, however, was largely forgotten as it was overshadowed by England's [[1966 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] victory later that year.\n\n==Records and statistics==\n\n===Individual records===\n\n====Most wins and final appearances====\nThe record for most FA Cup wins by a player is held by [[Ashley Cole]], who has won it seven times (with [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in 2002, 2003 and 2005, and [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in 2007, 2009, 2010 and 2012). With Chelsea's victory over Portsmouth in the [[2010 FA Cup Final|2010 final]], Cole beat the record of five jointly held by [[Charles Wollaston]] ([[Wanderers F.C.|Wanderers]]), [[Arthur Kinnaird, 11th Lord Kinnaird|Arthur Kinnaird]] ([[Wanderers F.C.|Wanderers]] & [[Old Etonians F.C.|Old Etonians]]) and [[Jimmy Forrest (footballer)|Jimmy Forrest]] ([[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]).\n\nCole has appeared in 8 finals, having also been on the losing side for Arsenal in 2001.\n\nThe record for most FA Cup wins by a manager is held by [[Ars\u00e8ne Wenger]], who won it seven times (with [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in 1998, 2002, 2003, 2005, 2014, 2015 and 2017.\n\n====Most goals====\nNotts County's [[Harry Cursham]] has scored the most goals in the FA Cup, with 49 goals in 44 appearances from 1877-91. Cursham has held the record continuously since 1887. The closest anyone has come to breaking this long-standing record was [[Ian Rush]], who scored 44 FA Cup goals in his career, from 1979-98.\n\nW. \"Doc\" Dowden scored 19 FA Cup goals for [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] in the 1929/30 season. This is believed to be the record for one individual in a season. For rounds proper only, the highest total is that of Albert Brown who scored 15 times for Tottenham in 1900/01.\n\nWhen [[Peter Osgood]] scored for Chelsea in the 1970 final, he became the last player to date (and ninth in total) to score in every round of the cup.\n\nIn one tie, between Bournemouth & Boscombe Athletic vs. Margate, [[Ted MacDougall]] scored 9 of Bournemouth's goals in their 11\u20130 victory.\n\n====Scoring firsts====\nIn 1876, [[Thomas Hughes (footballer)|Thomas Hughes]] was the first to score more than once in the final, in a replay match in which Wanderers defeated Old Etonians 3\u20130. In the same final, [[Alexander Bonsor]] from the losing side became the first to score in two consecutive finals (both of which his team lost).\n\n[[Eddie Kelly (footballer)|Eddie Kelly]] from Arsenal became the first substitute to score when he came on the pitch in the 70th minute of the 1971 final and scored in the 96th. [[Stuart McCall]] from Everton scored two goals after coming in from the bench in the 1989 final in the 90th and 102nd minutes.\n\nIn 2001, [[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.]] goalkeeper [[Tony Roberts (footballer)|Tony Roberts]] became the first goalkeeper in the history of the tournament to score a goal, this happened in a Fourth Round Qualifying game against [[Basingstoke Town]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/low/football/fa_cup/2695925.stm BBC News, 27 January 2003]</ref>\n\n====Scoring streaks====\nIn 1886, [[James Brown (footballer born 1862)|Jimmy Brown]] of [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] became the first to score in three consecutive finals from 1884 to 1886 (winning all three).\n\nIn 1887, Aston Villa legend [[Archie Hunter]] became the first player to score in every round of the FA Cup in Villa's victorious 1887 campaign (beginning from the second round, as Villa had a bye in the first). This feat was bettered in 1901 by [[Sandy Brown (Scottish footballer born 1879)|Sandy Brown]] of Tottenham Hotspur, who scored in all rounds from the first.\n\n[[File:Drogba chelsea.jpg|thumb|upright=0.85|In 2012, [[Didier Drogba]] of Chelsea became the first player to score in four FA Cup Finals]]\nIn the 2012 final, [[Didier Drogba]] became the first player to score in four FA Cup Finals.\n\n====Fastest goals====\n[[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa's]] [[Bob Chatt]] scored the winner in the [[1895 FA Cup Final]] with the then-fastest goal after just 30 seconds;<ref name=\"Chatt\">{{cite web|title=FA Cup Trivia |work=www.thefa.com |url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2003/05/48711.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20040106155319/http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2003/05/48711.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=6 January 2004 |accessdate=18 May 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> his record stood until broken by [[Louis Saha]] in [[2009 FA Cup Final|2009]], who scored in 25 seconds.<ref name = \"Saha\">{{cite news | title= Chelsea 2\u20131 Everton  | work= [[BBC Sport]]| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/8060989.stm| accessdate=31 May 2009 | date=30 May 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Louis Saha, Everton.jpg|thumb|upright=0.85|[[Louis Saha]] of Everton scored in a record 25 seconds in the [[2009 FA Cup Final]]]]\nOn 30 May 2009, [[Louis Saha]] scored the fastest ever goal in an FA Cup Final (after 25 seconds) for Everton, who lost 2\u20131 to eventual winners Chelsea.<ref name = \"Saha\"/>\n\nOn 13 February 2010, [[Jimmy Kebe]] of [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] scored the fastest goal in the FA Cup proper after just 9 seconds of Reading's Fifth Round tie against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]].<ref>[http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/FACompetitions/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/2010/quickest-goal-150210.aspx Quick goal in The Cup]</ref>\n\n====Hat\u2013tricks====\n[[William Townley]] scored the first hat\u2013trick in an FA Cup final for [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] when they beat [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C|Sheffield Wednesday]] 6\u20131 in [[1890 FA Cup Final|1890]].\n\nIn [[1894 FA Cup Final|1894]], [[James Logan (footballer, born 1870)|Jimmy Logan]] became the second player to score three goals in the final of the competition, with his [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] beating [[Bolton Wanderers F.C|Bolton Wanderers]] 4\u20131.\n\nThe third hat-trick in an FA Cup final was scored by [[Stan Mortensen]] for [[Blackpool F.C|Blackpool]] against [[Bolton Wanderers]] in the [[1953 FA Cup Final]].\n\nIn 1922, [[England national amateur football team|England amateur]] international Wilfred Minter created an unusual scoring record. In an era when there was some dispute whether or not a hat\u2013trick had to be scored as consecutive goals, Minter performed the feat twice in one match, as well as scoring a seventh, as he scored all of [[St Albans City F.C.|St Albans City]]'s goals against [[Dulwich Hamlet F.C.|Dulwich Hamlet]]. Despite his feat, they actually lost the game 8\u20137.<ref>{{cite book |last= Ward |first= Andrew |title= Soccer's Strangest Matches |year= 1992 |isbn= 0-86051-771-3 |pages=53\u201355}}</ref>\n\n====Penalties====\nThe first penalty in the final was not converted until 1910, with [[Albert Shepherd]] scoring from the spot in the Newcastle 2\u20130 Barnsley replay. The first missed penalty occurred in 1913, with [[Charlie Wallace]] from Aston Villa being the unlucky player, although Villa did win 1\u20130 over Sunderland. Two penalties were not converted until 1994, when [[Eric Cantona]] kicked from the spot in the 60th and 66th minutes to contribute to Manchester United's 4\u20130 win over Chelsea.\n\n[[File:Beasant.jpg|thumb|[[Dave Beasant]] of Wimbledon was the first goalkeeper to save a penalty in an FA Cup Final, in 1988]]\nIn 1988, [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]]'s [[Dave Beasant]] became the first goalkeeper to save a penalty in an [[FA Cup Final 1988|FA Cup final]] at Wembley, when he denied [[John Aldridge]] of [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] (although Charlie Wallace of Aston Villa was the first to miss a penalty in the final). Wimbledon defeated the league champions Liverpool 1\u20130 in that game, and so Beasant also became the first goalkeeper to captain an FA Cup-winning side.<ref>[http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2002/11/30680.htm At the Captain's Table: Dave Beasant] The FA, 15 November 2002</ref>\n\n====Own goals====\nIn 1877, [[Arthur Kinnaird, 11th Lord Kinnaird|Lord Kinnaird]] scored the first own goal in the final with Wanderers defeating Oxford University 2\u20131.\n\nIn [[1946 FA Cup Final|the 1946 final]], [[Bert Turner (footballer born 1909)|Bert Turner]] from Charlton Athletic became famous for scoring for both sides \u2013 first he put a goal in his own net, only to equalise from a free kick a minute later. Tommy Hutchison would repeat the feat (in reverse) for Manchester City in 1981.<ref name=\"Collett 2003 790\">{{cite book |last= Collett |first= Mike |title= The Complete Record of The FA Cup |year= 2003 |isbn= 1-899807-19-5 |pages=790}}</ref>\n\n====Age records====\n[[Billy Hampson]] of [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], the oldest FA Cup finalist, was 41 years and 257 days old when his side beat Aston Villa 2\u20130 in the 1924 Final.\n\nIn 1983 [[Norman Whiteside]], at 18, became the youngest player ever to score in an FA Cup final, whilst playing for Manchester United against [[brighton]]. As of 2017 this record remains unbroken.<ref>[http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/History/Postings/2006/01/FACupHistory_CupHeroes.htm FA Cup Heroes]{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} The FA, 13 January 2006</ref>\n\nIn 2004 [[Curtis Weston]] of [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] became the youngest ever player to play in the final at the age of 17 years and 119 days, beating the record of [[James F. M. Prinsep]] of [[Old Etonians F.C.|Old Etonians]] set in the [[1879 FA Cup Final|1879 Final]].\n\n====Disciplinary firsts====\nIn 1985, [[Kevin Moran (footballer)|Kevin Moran]] of [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] became the first player to be sent off in an FA Cup Final, he had fouled Peter Reid with a sliding tackle which missed the ball.<ref>[http://observer.guardian.co.uk/osm/story/0,,1720888,00.html Kevin Moran] The Observer, 5 March 2006</ref> United went on to win the match 1\u20130, after extra time. Since then, only four other players have been sent off in the FA Cup Final: [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio Reyes]] for [[Arsenal F.C.| Arsenal]] in 2005, [[Pablo Zabaleta]] for [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in 2013, [[Chris Smalling]] of Manchester United in 2016, and [[Victor Moses]] of Chelsea in 2017. Of these, only Moran received a straight red and Zabaleta and Moses ended up being on the losing side.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36292265</ref>\n\n====Accident firsts====\nAt the first Final in 1872, [[Edmund Cresswell]] broke his [[collarbone]] in a charge for Royal Engineers against Wanderers ten minutes into the match, but insisted on continuing play, in goal for the duration of the match, \"although completely disabled and in severe pain\", according to [[The Sportsman (1865 newspaper)|''The Sportsman'']]'s report.<ref>{{cite book|last=Warsop|first=Keith|title=The Early F.A. Cup Finals and the Southern Amateurs, A Who's Who and Match Facts 1872 to 1883|year=2004|publisher=Tony Brown Soccerdata|pages=40,71|isbn=1-899468-78-1}}</ref>\n\n[[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] left back [[Gerry Byrne (footballer, born 1938)|Gerry Byrne]] suffered an identical injury during the [[1965 FA Cup Final|1965 FA Cup final]] against [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]]. Byrne, who had a reputation for being as hard as nails, broke his [[collarbone]] as early as the 3rd minute. Despite being in agony, he played on for the next 87 minutes, and also an additional half hour of extra time. Despite the crippling injury he achieved legendary status, by not only helping [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] to win the cup for the first time in their history, following a 2-1 victory, but he also managed to provide an assist, breaking forward on the left and crossing for [[Roger Hunt]] to score the opening goal.\n\nIt has been otherwise commonplace for Cup Final players to continue playing despite injury. The first injured player forced to retire from a match was [[Arthur Dunn]] ([[Old Etonians F.C.|Old Etonians]]), who injured a knee 15 minutes into the second half against [[Blackburn Olympic F.C.|Blackburn Olympic]] in 1883. His team carried on playing with ten men but lost.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Early F.A. Cup Finals|page=53}}</ref>\n\n====Nationality firsts====\nIn 1872, [[Edward Ernest Bowen]] became the first non-Englishman to win the FA Cup. In 1873, [[Julian Sturgis]] was the first man from outside the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]] to win the Cup.\n\nIn 1996, [[Eric Cantona]] became the first non-British or Irish player to captain a winning side in the FA Cup Final.\n\nIn 1997, [[Ruud Gullit]] became the first overseas manager to win the FA Cup, as his Chelsea side beat Middlesbrough 2\u20130. [[Roberto Di Matteo]] scored what was then the fastest goal in a Wembley cup final, after 42 seconds.\n\n====Other individual firsts====\nIn the 1946 final, [[Arthur Turner (footballer born 1922)|Arthur Turner]], of Charlton Athletic, became the only player to play in the final who never played a League game for his club, since the [[the Football League|League's]] inception.<ref name=\"Collett 2003 790\"/>\n\nThe 2003 Final was the first in which a goalkeeper was substituted. [[Paul Jones (footballer, born 1967)|Paul Jones]] replaced the injured [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] goalkeeper [[Antti Niemi (footballer)|Antti Niemi]].\n\nIn the 2012 final, [[John Terry]] became the first player to captain the same team to four FA Cup victories.\n\n===Team records===\n\n====Most goals====\n[[File:Kettering Town v Boston United.jpg|thumb|James Brighton celebrates with Liam Canavan who scores for Kettering Town against Boston United - The club's 868th goal in the competition]]\n\nAs of 3 March 2020, [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]] hold the record for scoring the most number of goals in FA Cup history - netting a total of 891 times between 1888 and 2019, with [[Oliver Burgess|Ollie Burgess]] scoring the 800th goal against [[St Albans City F.C.|St Albans City]] on 11 October 2005 whilst going on to score a hat-trick. \n\n[[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] are second in the list with 883 goals. \n\n[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] are third with 874 goals.\n\nFourth are Manchester United on 868 goals. Fifth are Aston Villa on 846 goals.\n\n====Winning streaks====\nAfter winning the competition from 1884 to 1886, [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] became the second club to win three consecutive FA Cups and remain the only club still in existence to win \"three in a row\" to this day, as Wanderers, who achieved the feat 6 years earlier, were disbanded in 1883.\n\n[[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] hold the record for holding the FA Cup the longest, but only by virtue of the suspension of the competition for World War II.\n\n====Undefeated streaks====\nIn 2013, Chelsea set a record of 29 FA Cup matches without defeat (excluding penalty shoot-outs). Their loss to Manchester City in the 2013 semi-finals was their first since a quarter-final loss to Barnsley in 2008.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21921311 Chelsea 1\u20130 Man Utd]</ref>\n\nArsenal are currently the holders of the most FA Cup trophies (13).\n\n====Most final losses====\nIn 1969 Leicester City lost their fourth FA Cup Final, 1\u20130 to Manchester City. No other team has made it to the Final so many times without ever winning. However, 13 other teams have lost as many or more Finals but have also won the Cup at least once. The record number of Final defeats stands at 8 for Everton, although they have also won the Cup on 5 occasions.\n\n===Game records===\nOn 15 October 1887, [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] defeated [[Hyde F.C.|Hyde]] 26\u20130, which remains the record score in an FA Cup tie.\n\nIn 1903 [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] defeated [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] 6\u20130, a record that was matched by [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in 2019, when they defeated Watford 6-0. \n\nIn 1959, [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] became the first team to lose a player to injury in the Final and go on to win with 10 men, beating Luton Town 2\u20131 after having goalscorer [[Roy Dwight]] carried off with a broken leg after 33 minutes.\n\n1971 saw the longest tie in Cup history. [[Oxford City F.C.|Oxford City]] and [[Alvechurch F.C.|Alvechurch]] play 6 games for a total of 660 minutes. Alvechurch won the final game 1\u20130 to progress to the first round proper.\n\n====Tournament game streaks====\nIn 1963, [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] became the quickest winners of all time, apart from the special circumstances of [[1873 FA Cup Final|1873]]. They played their first match on 4 March, after 12 postponements, and won the final on 25 May, 82 days later.<ref>{{cite book |last= Collett |first= Mike |title= The Complete Record of The FA Cup |year= 2003 |isbn= 1-899807-19-5 |pages=782}}</ref>\n\nThe 1973\u201374 competition saw the record set for the highest number of games played in one season by one club. [[Bideford F.C.|Bideford]] played 13 games over five rounds: one for the 1st qualifying round, two for the 2nd qualifying round, five for the 3rd qualifying round, four for the 4th qualifying round, and one for the 1st round proper. Multiple replays no longer take place, so this record is unlikely to be beaten.\n\n===Competition records===\n1910 saw the start of a string of 14 consecutive finals (including 3 replays, thus 17 matches) in which the losing side failed to score. This series was not approached until 1994\u20132000, with seven consecutive finals (no replays).\n\nIn 1948, [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] became the only team to win the FA Cup after being drawn against top-division opposition in every round.\n\n1956\u201357 saw the record for highest number of rounds played in a row, when former League club [[New Brighton A.F.C.|New Brighton]] played in nine rounds. They started in the preliminary round, and progressed through four qualifying rounds to the fourth round proper, where they lost to [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]. They had just one replay \u2013 for their first round tie. The 1977\u201378 competition saw this record equalled by [[Blyth Spartans F.C.|Blyth Spartans]], who progressed from the 1st qualifying round to the 5th round proper. The games for the 2nd qualifying round and the 5th rounds proper went to a replay. The 1979\u201380 competition saw the record equalled again, this time by [[Harlow Town F.C.|Harlow Town]], who progressed from the Preliminary round through four qualifying rounds to the fourth round proper, where they lost to [[Watford F.C.|Watford]]. The matches for the 2nd and 3rd rounds went to a replay.\n\nIn 1959, [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] fielded the same 11 players in every round of the competition (9 matches including replays).\n\n1976\u201377 was the season with the largest number of matches (173) in the competition proper. Due to the abolition of multiple replays, the record is unlikely to be beaten. In seasons after 1996 (when penalty shootouts were introduced) the most ties (163) occurred in 2008\u201309.\n\nA record 763 clubs were accepted for the [[2011\u201312 FA Cup]].\n\n===Penalty shootouts===\nIn the 1971\u201372 competition, [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] became the first team to win a match in a [[penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]], beating [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] 4\u20133 after a 0\u20130 draw in the third-fourth playoff.<ref name=\"complete1\"/>\n\nThe [[2005 FA Cup Final]] between [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] was the first final ever to have to go to [[penalty shootout (football)|penalties]] as the score was still 0\u20130 after extra time. [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] won the shootout \u2013 and thus the Cup \u2013 5\u20134. It was the first 0\u20130 draw in an FA Cup final since 1912.\n\nOn 22 January 2008, [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] became the first club in the FA Cup to miss all four of their penalties in a penalty shootout, against [[Barnet FC|Barnet]] in a third round replay.<ref>\"[http://www.swindonadvertiser.co.uk/mostpopular.var.1989368.mostviewed.is_towns_spot_of_bother_a_record.php Is Town's spot of bother a record?]\" ''Swindon Advertiser''. URL last accessed 24 January 2008</ref>\n\n===Doubles/Trebles===\nIn 1889, Preston North End became the first club to achieve [[Double (association football)|the double]] of winning the FA Cup (beating [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] 3\u20130) and the Football League in the same season. This double was even more extraordinary in that the league was won without a single defeat, a feat which would not be repeated in the top division until 2003\u201304, by [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. Equally impressive was that the cup was won without conceding a single goal. Such was the team's dominance that it was nicknamed [[The Invincibles (football)|\"The Invincibles\"]].\n\nIn 1897 Aston Villa won the FA Cup and League Championship on same day, with results in League matches confirming their championship as they beat Everton 3\u20132 in the final.\n\n1961 saw [[Tottenham Hotspur]] become the first club in the 20th century to win the FA Cup and league championship in the same season, known famously as [[Double (association football)|The Double]]. They also retained the FA Cup the following year.\n\nIn 1986, [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] beat [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] 3\u20131 in the first all-[[Merseyside]] FA Cup final to complete the double and claim their first FA Cup triumph for 12 years. The teams would meet again in the final just 3 years later.\n\nIn 1994, [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] completed the double thanks to a 4\u20130 win over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] at Wembley. [[Eric Cantona]] scored two penalties and the other goals came from [[Mark Hughes]] and [[Brian McClair]].\n\nIn 1996, a late goal from [[Eric Cantona]] saw [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] become the first team to win the double twice as they beat [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] 1\u20130 at Wembley, a week after clinching the league title and overtake Tottenham's total of eight cup wins.\n\nIn 1998, [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] beat Newcastle 2\u20130. This was the second time Arsenal had done the domestic double, which includes winning the Premier League and FA Cup in the same year.\n\nIn 1999, Manchester United completed [[The Treble]] by also winning the [[Premier League|FA Premier League]] and the [[UEFA Champions League]].\n\nIn 2002, [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] matched [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]'s record of three doubles as they defeated [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] 2\u20130 at the [[Millennium Stadium]] and clinched the league title four days later.\n\nIn May 2010, Chelsea became the seventh club to complete the league and FA Cup \"[[Double (association football)#England|Double]]\", by beating [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] 1\u20130 in the 2010 final.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/8680493.stm Chelsea 1\u20130 Portsmouth]</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Manchester City became the first English side to win the [[Treble (association football)#Domestic trebles|domestic treble]] with their Cup win, having already secured the [[EFL Cup]] and the Premier League.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McNulty |first1=Phil |title=Man City 6-0 Watford: City clinch historic domestic treble |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48236232 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] also won the [[Welsh Cup]] in the year of their FA Cup win in 1927, becoming the only team in the world to achieve a transnational cup double.\n\n==Oddities==\nIn 1873, [[Sheffield F.C.|Sheffield]] confirmed a unique place in FA Cup history, knocking out [[Shropshire Wanderers F.C.|Shropshire Wanderers]] on the toss of a coin; the only time a tie has been decided in this way.<ref>{{cite book |last= Collett |first= Mike |title= The Complete Record of The FA Cup |year= 2003 |isbn= 1-899807-19-5 |page=537}}</ref>\n\nThe only game to be played on [[Christmas Day]] took place in 1888, [[Linfield F.C.|Linfield Athletic]] beating [[Cliftonville F.C.|Cliftonville]] 7\u20130.<ref name=\"Collett 2003 878\"/>\n\nIn 1921, [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham]] set the record for shortest FA Cup run \u2013 they forgot to send in their entry form.\n\nIn 1931 West Bromwich Albion became the only team to win the FA Cup and get promoted in the same season, defeating Birmingham City 2\u20131 in the final.\n\nIn 1990, [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] won the competition in a replay against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]. This was United manager [[Alex Ferguson]]'s first trophy at United, and this success is seen by many as having saved him from being dismissed after 4 unsuccessful seasons.\n\nFor the first time, the FA Cup was played under a roof in the final of the [[2002\u201303 in English football|2002\u201303 season]], held on 17 May 2003 at the [[Millennium Stadium]] in [[Cardiff]], with [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] benefiting from cover from the rain. Arsenal were 1\u20130 winners.\n\n[[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] became the first side to win the FA Cup and be relegated in the same season, after beating [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] 1\u20130 in the [[2013 FA Cup Final|2013 final]]. Their fate in the Premier League was sealed three days after their triumph, following a 4\u20131 defeat to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22430454 | work=BBC News | title=Arsenal 4\u20131 Wigan | date=14 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Participants==\n\n===Amateur, university and professional teams===\nIn 1883 [[Blackburn Olympic F.C.|Blackburn Olympic]] broke the \"old order of things\" to defeat [[Old Etonians F.C.|Old Etonians]] in the final to become the first professional club to win the trophy. The win marked a turning point in the culture of the game in England.\n\nIn 2002, [[Team Bath F.C.|Team Bath]] (from the [[University of Bath]]) became the first university team to enter the competition since [[Gonville & Caius A.F.C.|Gonville & Caius]] in 1881, and progressed through the qualifying rounds before being knocked out in the first round proper by [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]].\n\n===Scottish sides===\nIn 1884 and 1885 Scottish side [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]] reached the final, the first time a non-English side had done so. They lost both times. (Scotland had had its own [[Scottish Cup]] since 1873.) (See also: [[Scottish clubs in the FA Cup]])\n\n===Welsh sides===\nIn 1914 [[Swansea City F.C.|Swansea Town]] became the first club from South Wales to reach the second round. They were beaten 2\u20131 by QPR.\n\nThe 1927 final resulted in a [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] victory over [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. To the present day, Cardiff City are the only non-English-based team to win the trophy.\n\n==Traditions==\n\n===Ribbons===\nIn 1901, Tottenham became the first team to attach ribbons in their team colours to the trophy, a tradition that continues to this day.\n\n===Equipment===\nIn the 1933 final, Everton players wore shirts numbered 1\u201311, and Manchester City players 12\u201322. This was the first major competitive game ever to have the players' shirts numbered.\n\nThe [[FA Cup Final 1973|1973 FA Cup Final]] was the first that a yellow ball was used in a Cup Final (although an orange ball had been used in previous finals, for example in 1968).  An orange ball was used in the [[2014 FA Cup Final|2014]] and [[2015 FA Cup Final|2015 Cup Final]]s, as they were used throughout the competition.\n\n===Referees===\nSince 1902, referees can only officiate one Cup Final, though they are allowed to have prior Final experience as an assistant referee.\n\n===Royal attendance===\nIn 1914, [[George V of the United Kingdom|George V]] became the first monarch to watch the FA Cup Final between [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the last cup final played at [[Crystal Palace National Sports Centre|Crystal Palace]].\n\nThe 'Matthews Final' of 1953 was the first football match attended by [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|The Queen]], in her Coronation year.<ref>[http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/page4829.asp 80 facts about the Queen] British Monarchy</ref>\n\n===Triangular corner flags===\nIt is commonly held that previous winners of the FA Cup are traditionally the only clubs allowed to use [[triangular corner flags in English football]]. However, this tradition is not affirmed in the FA's lawbook.\n\n==Greatest goals==\nThe 1981 final contained what many consider to be the greatest ever final goal,<ref>[http://football.guardian.co.uk/pictures/image/0,8556,-10604601121,00.html Best ever FA cup final goal] The Guardian, 7 February 2003</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/sports_talk/1765630.stm Your favourite FA Cup goal] BBC Sport, 17 January 2002</ref> scored by Tottenham's [[Ricky Villa]] who beat several players in a mazy run before slotting the ball home.\n\nIn 1999, [[Ryan Giggs]] of Manchester United scored in [[extra time]] to defeat Arsenal 2\u20131 in FA Cup semi-final replay. The goal was voted the greatest in FA Cup history in 2003.<ref>[http://www.icons.org.uk/theicons/collection/fa-cup/features/greatest-fa-cup-goals The Greatest FA Cup Goals] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090822000000/http://www.icons.org.uk/theicons/collection/fa-cup/features/greatest-fa-cup-goals |date=22 August 2009 }} Icons</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n===Bibliography===\n{{cite book |title=We Won the Cup: A Celebration for the 100th F.A.Cup Final|date= 10 April 1981|first= David |last=Barber |publisher=Pan Books|isbn= 978-0330264013 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{FA Cup Seasons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of The Fa Cup}}\n[[Category:FA Cup]]\n[[Category:History of football in England]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: second level \u2192 second-level, 2-1 \u2192 2\u20131, 1877-91 \u2192 1877\u201391 (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_FA_Cup"}
